1
00:02:34,655 --> 00:02:38,199
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

2
00:02:40,786 --> 00:02:42,119
Liberty's moving.

3
00:02:42,287 --> 00:02:44,539
The 10:15 has been moved
to the Indian Treaty Room.

4
00:02:44,706 --> 00:02:49,335
- Ten-fifteen is American Fisheries?
- They're giving you a 200-pound halibut.

5
00:02:49,503 --> 00:02:53,923
Janie, make a note. We need more events
where somebody gives me a really big fish.

6
00:02:54,091 --> 00:02:55,883
- Yes, sir.
- Janie, I'm kidding.

7
00:02:56,051 --> 00:02:57,510
- Of course, sir.
- Hey, Cooper.

8
00:02:57,678 --> 00:02:59,428
Morning, Mr. President.

9
00:03:00,639 --> 00:03:03,891
Mr. Rothschild asked to have a moment
with you this morning, sir.

10
00:03:04,059 --> 00:03:06,394
Is he upset about the speech last night?

11
00:03:06,562 --> 00:03:08,688
He seemed concerned.

12
00:03:08,856 --> 00:03:12,024
Well, it wouldn't be a Monday morning
unless Lewis was concerned...

13
00:03:12,192 --> 00:03:14,318
...about something I did Sunday night.

14
00:03:14,862 --> 00:03:17,405
- You skipped the paragraph.
- And Monday morning, it is.

15
00:03:17,573 --> 00:03:20,950
"Americans can no longer afford to pretend
they live in a great society."

16
00:03:21,118 --> 00:03:23,870
And then nothing.
You dumped the handguns paragraph.

17
00:03:24,037 --> 00:03:26,038
SHEPHERD:
This is a time for prudence, Lewis.

18
00:03:26,206 --> 00:03:28,207
LEWIS:
But, sir, that was the kick-ass section.

19
00:03:28,375 --> 00:03:30,877
Well, I thought,
what with being president and all...

20
00:03:31,044 --> 00:03:34,881
- I'm sorry, sir. I didn't mean to imply...
- I thought you'd be turning cartwheels.

21
00:03:35,048 --> 00:03:36,591
Sixty-three percent job approval.

22
00:03:36,758 --> 00:03:38,759
LEWIS: That is good news.
- Morning, Mr. President.

23
00:03:38,927 --> 00:03:40,469
- Charlie.
- Morning, Charlie.

24
00:03:40,888 --> 00:03:42,889
LEWIS: Sir, the press
is gonna need an explanation.

25
00:03:43,056 --> 00:03:46,058
SHEPHERD: For what?
- You dumped the whole kick-ass section.

26
00:03:46,226 --> 00:03:48,686
Now we've just got this thing
hanging out there.

27
00:03:48,854 --> 00:03:50,229
There's this "thing"?

28
00:03:50,397 --> 00:03:53,566
"Americans can't afford to pretend
they live in a great society"...

29
00:03:53,734 --> 00:03:56,319
No explanation, no context,
just this thing.

30
00:03:56,486 --> 00:03:59,488
- And it's hanging out there.
- Yes, sir.

31
00:03:59,656 --> 00:04:00,781
- Maria.
MARIA: Morning, sir.

32
00:04:00,949 --> 00:04:04,243
- Did they tell you I'll need the consumer...
- Overall consumer spending.

33
00:04:04,411 --> 00:04:06,245
- We'll have it in 15 minutes.
SHEPHERD: Thanks.

34
00:04:06,705 --> 00:04:11,208
- Mr. President, we need to focus on...
- Lewis, reduce your morning coffee by half.

35
00:04:11,376 --> 00:04:12,585
I don't drink coffee, sir.

36
00:04:12,753 --> 00:04:15,421
Hit yourself over the head
with a baseball bat, would you?

37
00:04:15,589 --> 00:04:17,256
LEWIS: Yes, sir.
- Happy birthday, Laura.

38
00:04:17,424 --> 00:04:19,050
- Laura, happy birthday.
- Thank you.

39
00:04:19,217 --> 00:04:21,302
- I should send her flowers.
- You did, sir.

40
00:04:21,470 --> 00:04:22,637
- Good.
CHAPIL: Good morning.

41
00:04:22,804 --> 00:04:25,222
- How are you today, Mrs. Chapil?
- Fine, thank you.

42
00:04:25,390 --> 00:04:28,184
Mr. Kodak left a detailed breakdown
of the approval poll for you.

43
00:04:28,352 --> 00:04:30,269
He seemed to indicate
that it was good news.

44
00:04:30,437 --> 00:04:32,521
Sixty-three percent of it, at any rate.

45
00:04:32,689 --> 00:04:36,359
Lucy called. You forgot to sign
her permission slip for her class.

46
00:04:36,610 --> 00:04:38,152
Uh, the museum trip. I'll get it.

47
00:04:38,320 --> 00:04:40,363
- What time's she getting home?
- Three-twenty.

48
00:04:40,530 --> 00:04:42,281
- How's my afternoon?
- Very crowded.

49
00:04:42,449 --> 00:04:44,116
Schedule some time at 3:45.

50
00:04:44,284 --> 00:04:45,868
[SPEAKS IN SPANISH]

51
00:04:46,036 --> 00:04:48,412
SHEPHERD:
Too Tall McCall. So how was Mexico?

52
00:04:48,580 --> 00:04:50,289
[IN ENGLISH]
I didn't truly appreciate it...

53
00:04:50,457 --> 00:04:52,833
...till I discovered
that America isn't a great society.

54
00:04:53,126 --> 00:04:56,671
- He dumped the whole section.
- There's this, uh, thing hanging out there.

55
00:04:56,922 --> 00:04:58,130
Not a great society, sir?

56
00:04:58,298 --> 00:05:01,425
With you away it wasn't.
Now that you're back we're great again.

57
00:05:01,843 --> 00:05:04,679
Well, the press is saying,
"What did he mean by that?"

58
00:05:04,846 --> 00:05:06,430
A.J., did you get one of these?

59
00:05:06,848 --> 00:05:08,808
Is that the letter from Solomon
at the GDC?

60
00:05:08,976 --> 00:05:12,687
It's from the environmental community.
These people are out of control.

61
00:05:12,854 --> 00:05:14,271
Well, they're frustrated.

62
00:05:14,439 --> 00:05:16,774
Are they blaming the president
for global warming?

63
00:05:16,942 --> 00:05:18,609
Well, they don't think he caused it.

64
00:05:18,777 --> 00:05:23,030
I'm on the phone with them twice a week.
I honestly don't know what they want.

65
00:05:23,198 --> 00:05:25,866
They want a 20 percent reduction
in fossil-fuel emissions.

66
00:05:26,034 --> 00:05:28,869
- Won't pass at 20 percent.
- Well, we haven't really tried.

67
00:05:29,037 --> 00:05:31,914
Lewis, McSorley, McCluskey and Shane
hold too many markers.

68
00:05:32,082 --> 00:05:34,041
If we try to push this through and lose...

69
00:05:34,209 --> 00:05:36,502
...there'll be a loud thud
when we hit the ground.

70
00:05:36,670 --> 00:05:38,754
That's not what you want
in an election year.

71
00:05:38,922 --> 00:05:40,631
Talk to GDC again, A.J.

72
00:05:40,799 --> 00:05:44,260
Tell them I resent the implication
I've turned my back on the environment.

73
00:05:44,428 --> 00:05:46,387
Tell them I'll send 455 to the floor...

74
00:05:46,555 --> 00:05:49,098
...but I'm gonna ask
for a 10 percent reduction.

75
00:05:49,266 --> 00:05:51,058
They wanna pull their support, fine.

76
00:05:51,226 --> 00:05:54,603
With a 63 percent job approval rating,
I don't need their help.

77
00:05:54,771 --> 00:05:57,898
- Good deal.
- All right, let's get going. Where's Leon?

78
00:05:58,066 --> 00:06:01,569
John, will you call Mr. Kodak
and tell him the president's waiting?

79
00:06:01,737 --> 00:06:03,112
JOHN:
Oh, sorry, my fault.

80
00:06:03,822 --> 00:06:05,406
Never mind, John.

81
00:06:05,991 --> 00:06:07,700
Excuse me.

82
00:06:08,410 --> 00:06:10,369
- Morning, Mr. President.
SHEPHERD: You all right?

83
00:06:10,537 --> 00:06:12,413
They keep moving that big ficus plant.

84
00:06:12,581 --> 00:06:13,748
[ALL CHUCKLE]

85
00:06:13,915 --> 00:06:15,458
We're all here, Mr. President.

86
00:06:15,625 --> 00:06:18,669
Okay, first of all,
I wanted to say congratulations.

87
00:06:18,837 --> 00:06:22,631
Three years ago we were elected
by one of the narrowest margins in history.

88
00:06:22,799 --> 00:06:24,842
And today Kodak, here, tells us...

89
00:06:25,010 --> 00:06:27,970
...63 percent of registered voters
think we're doing a good job.

90
00:06:28,138 --> 00:06:30,389
Wait. You wanted me to poll
registered voters?

91
00:06:30,557 --> 00:06:31,766
[ALL CHUCKLE]

92
00:06:31,933 --> 00:06:34,268
The poll also tells us
what we already know:

93
00:06:34,436 --> 00:06:36,729
If we don't get our crime bill
through Congress...

94
00:06:36,897 --> 00:06:38,689
...those numbers are gonna be memory.

95
00:06:38,857 --> 00:06:41,233
So, starting today,
we're shifting it into gear.

96
00:06:41,401 --> 00:06:44,737
- Can I tell the press that gun control...
A. J: Crime control, Robin.

97
00:06:44,905 --> 00:06:47,448
Gun control means we're wimps
and soft on crime.

98
00:06:47,616 --> 00:06:48,616
- Hang on.
- Lewis.

99
00:06:48,784 --> 00:06:50,785
We're not putting back
handgun restrictions?

100
00:06:50,952 --> 00:06:52,745
No. We're leaving them out.

101
00:06:53,497 --> 00:06:56,207
Mr. President,
we campaigned on this issue.

102
00:06:56,374 --> 00:06:59,794
We took them out in the low 40s,
but we could push it through now.

103
00:06:59,961 --> 00:07:01,754
After the elections, Lewis.

104
00:07:02,297 --> 00:07:04,548
We may never have
an opportunity like this again.

105
00:07:04,716 --> 00:07:08,344
Sir, let's take this 63 percent out for a spin.
Let's see what it could do.

106
00:07:08,512 --> 00:07:11,180
We can't take it for a spin.
We need it to get re-elected.

107
00:07:11,348 --> 00:07:15,518
For reasons passing understanding,
they don't relate guns to gun-related crime.

108
00:07:15,685 --> 00:07:18,646
Robin, you can brief the press
this afternoon. As of today...

109
00:07:18,814 --> 00:07:21,982
...the crime bill is priority one
on the president's domestic agenda.

110
00:07:22,150 --> 00:07:23,943
- Got it.
- Leon, you run the war room.

111
00:07:24,111 --> 00:07:27,613
We're gonna need detailed projections
for all the target districts.

112
00:07:27,781 --> 00:07:31,242
Oh, and, Leon, don't be the nice,
sweet guy from Brooklyn on this.

113
00:07:31,409 --> 00:07:32,660
Do what the NRA does.

114
00:07:32,828 --> 00:07:34,245
- Scare them?
A. J: Exactly.

115
00:07:34,412 --> 00:07:35,496
I can do that, heh.

116
00:07:35,664 --> 00:07:39,291
Lewis, you're legislative liaison.
You're gonna run the show on the hill.

117
00:07:39,543 --> 00:07:43,379
Can I just say that it might be easier
to fight a war on drugs...

118
00:07:43,547 --> 00:07:47,633
...if we weren't arming drug dealers?
- We gotta fight the fights we can win.

119
00:07:47,801 --> 00:07:49,009
Yes, sir.

120
00:07:49,177 --> 00:07:50,886
A. J:
We want to announce the crime bill...

121
00:07:51,054 --> 00:07:53,389
...at the State of the Union,
72 days from today.

122
00:07:53,557 --> 00:07:55,641
Last notice count put us 18 votes short.

123
00:07:55,809 --> 00:07:59,186
Eighteen votes in 72 days.
Thank you, everyone.

124
00:07:59,354 --> 00:08:01,021
ALL: Thank you.
- Janie, what's next?

125
00:08:01,189 --> 00:08:03,023
Security briefing, sir.

126
00:08:04,234 --> 00:08:06,569
[HORNS HONKING]

127
00:08:07,279 --> 00:08:09,071
[PHONE RINGS]

128
00:08:09,698 --> 00:08:11,907
WOMAN:
Morning, Global Defense Council.

129
00:08:12,951 --> 00:08:14,535
You wanted to see me?

130
00:08:14,703 --> 00:08:17,788
- I just got off the phone with A.J.
- The president read the letter?

131
00:08:17,956 --> 00:08:20,708
The president's pissed.
That letter was a stupid move.

132
00:08:20,876 --> 00:08:23,627
- We should stand by every word of it.
- This isn't the guy...

133
00:08:23,795 --> 00:08:27,047
...who needed our help four years ago.
He's incredibly popular.

134
00:08:27,215 --> 00:08:30,426
He's gonna win re-election.
He could give a shit what we stand by.

135
00:08:31,303 --> 00:08:35,055
If he passes the most important piece
of environmental legislation in history...

136
00:08:35,223 --> 00:08:38,684
...despite our negative endorsement,
our political weight in the future...

137
00:08:38,852 --> 00:08:41,770
...will rank somewhere below
the Save the Spotted Owl Society.

138
00:08:45,775 --> 00:08:47,026
I'm bringing in some help.

139
00:08:47,194 --> 00:08:50,529
Heh, we don't need another expert
to confirm what everyone already knows.

140
00:08:50,697 --> 00:08:52,114
Not an environmental expert.

141
00:08:52,282 --> 00:08:54,909
A professional political strategist.

142
00:08:55,118 --> 00:08:57,912
We are playing hardball with
Andrew Shepherd and we need a heavy bat.

143
00:08:58,538 --> 00:09:00,998
- Who?
- Sydney Ellen Wade.

144
00:09:01,166 --> 00:09:05,294
Gah, christ, she doesn't know the first
thing about the environmental lobby.

145
00:09:05,462 --> 00:09:08,464
She's a closer, Susan.
She gets the job done.

146
00:09:09,132 --> 00:09:10,633
SHEPHERD:
What if I lose this?

147
00:09:10,800 --> 00:09:12,468
LEWIS:
Then move this up here.

148
00:09:12,636 --> 00:09:14,094
Sasser from the Times called.

149
00:09:14,262 --> 00:09:16,388
Wanted to know what
a "great society" was.

150
00:09:16,556 --> 00:09:17,556
What'd you tell him?

151
00:09:17,724 --> 00:09:20,601
I can't speak for the president,
but for my money, Bermuda.

152
00:09:20,769 --> 00:09:21,769
Perfect.

153
00:09:21,937 --> 00:09:25,522
Your cousin Judith got the flu and
won't be able to join you Thursday night.

154
00:09:25,690 --> 00:09:28,067
I'm sorry to hear that.
Remind me to call her later.

155
00:09:28,235 --> 00:09:29,235
Yes, sir.

156
00:09:29,402 --> 00:09:31,153
- You're gonna go stag?
- Not a problem.

157
00:09:31,321 --> 00:09:34,782
No, we've never gone wrong parading
you around as the lonely widower.

158
00:09:39,496 --> 00:09:40,829
I can't believe I said that.

159
00:09:41,665 --> 00:09:43,249
That was a thoughtless remark.

160
00:09:43,416 --> 00:09:46,377
I wouldn't never dream of insulting you
or your wife's memory.

161
00:09:46,544 --> 00:09:48,963
That's okay. Forget it. What time is it?

162
00:09:49,923 --> 00:09:51,048
It's 3:30, sir.

163
00:09:51,591 --> 00:09:53,550
I'm gonna go up and say hi to Lucy.

164
00:09:53,718 --> 00:09:56,637
Ah, you have the attorney general at 4
and the trade rep at 4:30.

165
00:09:56,805 --> 00:09:58,639
And you promised NPR five minutes.

166
00:09:58,807 --> 00:10:00,683
- Mr. President...
- Robin...

167
00:10:00,850 --> 00:10:02,559
Don't worry about it.

168
00:10:06,398 --> 00:10:09,400
[TROMBONE HONKING]

169
00:10:24,416 --> 00:10:26,875
Well, don't stop. It sounds great.
What is it?

170
00:10:27,919 --> 00:10:29,044
Scales.

171
00:10:29,671 --> 00:10:31,714
Well, you're playing with gusto.

172
00:10:31,965 --> 00:10:34,216
- Are my lips swollen?
- Are they supposed to be?

173
00:10:34,384 --> 00:10:36,427
- Yeah.
- Yeah, well, you're doing just fine.

174
00:10:36,594 --> 00:10:39,930
- What you got behind your back?
- I have a little surprise for you.

175
00:10:40,473 --> 00:10:43,225
- Is it a dirt bike?
- No, ha, ha.

176
00:10:44,769 --> 00:10:46,812
Hmm.

177
00:10:46,980 --> 00:10:49,565
Is it a really old, seventh grade textbook
of yours...

178
00:10:49,733 --> 00:10:53,152
...that you want me to read and discuss
at dinner and drive me crazy with?

179
00:10:53,320 --> 00:10:56,322
Well, I'm not comfortable with the
"really old" part, but the rest was true.

180
00:10:56,489 --> 00:10:57,531
[LUCY GROANS]

181
00:10:57,699 --> 00:10:59,575
Understanding the Constitution.

182
00:10:59,743 --> 00:11:03,871
Your social studies teacher said you'll be
studying the Constitution this week.

183
00:11:04,039 --> 00:11:05,581
Wait, you talked to Mr. Linder?

184
00:11:05,749 --> 00:11:10,711
Yes, it's called a parent-teacher conference
and Mr. Linder and I were the key players.

185
00:11:11,588 --> 00:11:13,547
So why don't you like social studies,
Luce?

186
00:11:14,132 --> 00:11:15,132
I like it fine, Dad.

187
00:11:15,300 --> 00:11:19,011
Oh, come on, all your other teachers say
you're happy and enthusiastic.

188
00:11:19,179 --> 00:11:22,014
Mr. Linder says you never participate
unless he calls on you.

189
00:11:22,182 --> 00:11:24,141
Even then, it's a one-word answer.

190
00:11:25,518 --> 00:11:29,104
I don't know, Dad.
I guess I'm just not...

191
00:11:31,149 --> 00:11:32,524
I don't know.

192
00:11:32,692 --> 00:11:33,859
Luce...

193
00:11:34,027 --> 00:11:37,363
Take a look at this book.
This is exciting stuff.

194
00:11:37,530 --> 00:11:40,866
It's about who we are and what we want.

195
00:11:41,034 --> 00:11:43,285
Read what it says on the first page.

196
00:11:44,621 --> 00:11:46,330
"Property of Gilmore Junior High."

197
00:11:46,498 --> 00:11:48,791
The next page, Luce.

198
00:11:50,794 --> 00:11:53,212
"We, the people of the United States...

199
00:11:53,380 --> 00:11:56,840
...in order to form a perfect union"...
- It grabs you right away.

200
00:11:57,008 --> 00:11:58,050
This is a page-turner.

201
00:11:59,427 --> 00:12:00,552
I can't wait.

202
00:12:00,720 --> 00:12:03,847
Well, good. It's possible this subject
may come up at dinner.

203
00:12:04,015 --> 00:12:06,141
Do you see it as part of your job
to torture me?

204
00:12:06,309 --> 00:12:08,769
No, just one of the perks.
See you tonight.

205
00:12:08,937 --> 00:12:10,020
Yeah.

206
00:12:10,188 --> 00:12:12,189
[PLAYING "HAIL TO THE CHIEF"]

207
00:12:18,071 --> 00:12:20,531
The C-STAD hardware's
been in place for a month.

208
00:12:20,698 --> 00:12:23,534
We have 22 instructors
from the Army Air Defense School...

209
00:12:23,701 --> 00:12:25,661
...waiting to go and train the Israelis.

210
00:12:25,829 --> 00:12:27,413
How soon can you deploy them?

211
00:12:27,580 --> 00:12:31,291
We can airlift them by morning.
They'll have C-STAD operational in 20 days.

212
00:12:31,459 --> 00:12:32,835
Any security concerns?

213
00:12:33,002 --> 00:12:35,671
If anybody wanted to hit it,
they'd have hit it by now.

214
00:12:35,839 --> 00:12:37,965
Okay, let's move on it.
Thank you, gentlemen.

215
00:12:38,133 --> 00:12:39,883
[MEN CHATTERING]

216
00:12:40,051 --> 00:12:41,885
MAN: Good night, gentlemen.
- Thank you.

217
00:12:43,138 --> 00:12:45,931
- Good seeing you. Good night.
- You too. Good night.

218
00:12:46,099 --> 00:12:49,393
Have a good evening, Mrs. Chapil.
Janie, I'll see you tomorrow morning.

219
00:12:49,561 --> 00:12:52,062
- You will.
- Good night, Janie. Night, Mrs. Chapil.

220
00:12:52,272 --> 00:12:53,605
- Mr. President, sir.
- Thank you.

221
00:12:53,773 --> 00:12:55,065
[SHEPHERD SIGHS]

222
00:12:55,233 --> 00:12:57,734
Leo Solomon brought in
a hired gun at the GDC.

223
00:12:57,902 --> 00:13:00,070
- It's about time.
- She's a lawyer from Virginia.

224
00:13:00,238 --> 00:13:02,739
Her name is Sydney Ellen Wade.
I know her pretty well.

225
00:13:02,907 --> 00:13:05,409
She's had a lot of success
getting congressmen elected.

226
00:13:05,577 --> 00:13:07,703
- Maybe we should try to steal her, heh.
- Ha, ha.

227
00:13:07,871 --> 00:13:11,457
Ten percent. Don't let them
leave the room till they're clear about that.

228
00:13:11,624 --> 00:13:13,208
A. J:
Yes, sir.

229
00:13:13,376 --> 00:13:15,919
If you've got a free second,
stop in and say hello.

230
00:13:16,087 --> 00:13:17,254
It might smooth the way.

231
00:13:17,422 --> 00:13:19,756
SHEPHERD: Mention it to Janie tomorrow.
A. J: Good deal.

232
00:13:19,924 --> 00:13:22,885
SHEPHERD: Let's clear this off the table
and focus on the crime bill.

233
00:13:23,052 --> 00:13:26,346
I don't want to just win.
I want to win by a couple of touchdowns.

234
00:13:26,514 --> 00:13:28,390
We will, Mr. President.

235
00:13:28,933 --> 00:13:30,893
- A. J?
- Sir.

236
00:13:31,060 --> 00:13:33,854
Robin said something to me today...

237
00:13:34,022 --> 00:13:36,273
...and I know
she wouldn't have said it if, uh...

238
00:13:37,275 --> 00:13:40,319
I mean, she wasn't saying it to me,
I realize.

239
00:13:43,615 --> 00:13:46,825
- Forget it. I'll see you in the morning.
- Good night, Mr. President.

240
00:13:46,993 --> 00:13:48,285
- A. J?
- Yes, sir?

241
00:13:48,453 --> 00:13:52,414
When we're out of the office
and alone, you can call me Andy.

242
00:13:53,041 --> 00:13:54,041
I beg your pardon?

243
00:13:54,209 --> 00:13:57,544
You were the best man at my wedding,
for crying out loud. Call me Andy.

244
00:13:57,712 --> 00:14:00,756
Whatever you say, Mr. President.
Good night, sir.

245
00:14:01,466 --> 00:14:03,258
Good night, A.J.

246
00:14:16,940 --> 00:14:19,691
- Hi. I'm Sydney Ellen Wade.
- He needs your driver's license.

247
00:14:19,859 --> 00:14:21,360
- From Virginia.
- He doesn't care.

248
00:14:21,528 --> 00:14:24,154
- I'm meeting with Mr. Maclnerney.
- He doesn't need to know that.

249
00:14:24,322 --> 00:14:26,740
Oh, forgive me.

250
00:14:26,908 --> 00:14:29,159
This is my first time at the White House.

251
00:14:29,327 --> 00:14:33,205
- I'm trying to savor the Capra-esque quality.
- He doesn't know what that means.

252
00:14:33,373 --> 00:14:36,291
Yeah, I do. Frank Capra.
Great American director.

253
00:14:36,459 --> 00:14:39,545
It's a Wonderful Life,
Mr. Smith Goes to Washington.

254
00:14:39,963 --> 00:14:43,048
Sydney Ellen Wade of Virginia,
knock them dead.

255
00:14:43,841 --> 00:14:45,050
Thanks.

256
00:14:45,885 --> 00:14:49,846
We'll start subsidizing private schools
the day we give up on public education.

257
00:14:50,014 --> 00:14:53,725
I know the proposal only scratches
the surface, but it's the least we can do.

258
00:14:53,893 --> 00:14:56,603
We'll let Harold look at it.
We'll revisit it next week.

259
00:14:56,771 --> 00:14:59,523
Jerry, say hello to Linda for me.
Have a good Thanksgiving.

260
00:14:59,691 --> 00:15:01,692
Thank you, Mr. President. Thank you.

261
00:15:03,152 --> 00:15:05,821
- How are we doing?
- You're four minutes ahead of schedule.

262
00:15:05,989 --> 00:15:07,030
- Ahead?
- Yes, sir.

263
00:15:07,198 --> 00:15:09,866
That's unprecedented.
I don't know what to do with myself.

264
00:15:10,034 --> 00:15:13,579
- Mr. Maclnerney asked me to remind you...
- Oh, the GDC meeting. Yeah.

265
00:15:13,871 --> 00:15:16,707
Rest assured your concerns
are not falling on deaf ears.

266
00:15:16,874 --> 00:15:20,711
The environmental lobby has known
no greater ally than President Shepherd.

267
00:15:20,878 --> 00:15:23,880
Hardly an impressive distinction, A.J.

268
00:15:24,173 --> 00:15:27,134
Sydney, we should leave Mr. Maclnerney
alone now. He's already...

269
00:15:27,302 --> 00:15:29,553
He doesn't want us to leave him alone...

270
00:15:29,721 --> 00:15:33,432
...because Mr. Maclnerney has not yet done
what he needs to do today.

271
00:15:35,018 --> 00:15:39,354
Sir, uh, Miss Wade's been thrown into
the deep end of the pool on her first day.

272
00:15:39,522 --> 00:15:43,692
She hasn't even had a chance to read
the report of the Quebec Conference.

273
00:15:43,860 --> 00:15:45,777
You're right. I haven't read it.

274
00:15:45,945 --> 00:15:48,447
If someone asked me yesterday,
I would've told them...

275
00:15:48,615 --> 00:15:50,907
...that it was made up
of six professional hockey teams.

276
00:15:51,075 --> 00:15:52,117
[ALL CHUCKLE]

277
00:15:52,285 --> 00:15:56,580
But what I do know is that it's time
for the president to run for president again.

278
00:15:56,748 --> 00:15:59,875
Kodak is as good as it gets
when it comes to electoral strategy.

279
00:16:00,043 --> 00:16:02,377
I'm sure he's told the president
what I'd tell him:

280
00:16:02,545 --> 00:16:06,715
Grab Michigan and California, where they
make cars, planes and burn fossil fuels.

281
00:16:06,883 --> 00:16:09,468
But if I'd read these 800 pages
I would've discovered...

282
00:16:09,636 --> 00:16:12,971
...that the burning of fossil fuels
is responsible for global warming...

283
00:16:13,181 --> 00:16:15,807
...and the 20 percent reduction
recommended by the GDC...

284
00:16:15,975 --> 00:16:19,311
...is a step toward arresting
the catastrophic greenhouse effect...

285
00:16:19,479 --> 00:16:21,813
...which has gone unchecked
by this administration.

286
00:16:21,981 --> 00:16:25,067
SUSAN: It's time to...
- The chief of staff won't let us leave...

287
00:16:25,234 --> 00:16:27,569
...until he's broken the bad news.

288
00:16:31,032 --> 00:16:35,160
I'm afraid Sydney's right, although
not about Michigan and California.

289
00:16:35,328 --> 00:16:39,289
The president asked me to convey to you
he's sending his energy bill to the floor...

290
00:16:39,457 --> 00:16:42,626
...with a call for a 10 percent reduction.

291
00:16:42,919 --> 00:16:45,337
The president is willing
to go it alone on this...

292
00:16:45,505 --> 00:16:49,007
...but he's asking... Frankly,
he's expecting the full support of the GDC.

293
00:16:49,550 --> 00:16:51,426
He is expecting our full support?

294
00:16:51,594 --> 00:16:53,553
- Yes, he is.
- The president's dreaming.

295
00:16:53,721 --> 00:16:56,306
The president has critically
misjudged reality.

296
00:16:56,474 --> 00:16:58,433
If he thinks
the environmental community...

297
00:16:58,601 --> 00:17:01,311
...is gonna whistle a happy tune
while rallying support...

298
00:17:01,479 --> 00:17:04,564
...around this lame mockery
of environmental leadership...

299
00:17:04,732 --> 00:17:07,901
...just because he's nice
and done better than his predecessors...

300
00:17:08,069 --> 00:17:10,654
...then your boss is the chief executive
of Fantasyland.

301
00:17:10,822 --> 00:17:13,240
Let's take him out back
and beat the shit out of him.

302
00:17:13,408 --> 00:17:16,076
- Morning, Mr. President. How are you?
- Couldn't be better.

303
00:17:16,244 --> 00:17:19,871
My apologies for the interruption.
A.J. Suggested I come by and say hello.

304
00:17:20,623 --> 00:17:23,333
You wouldn't be Sydney Ellen Wade
by any chance, would you?

305
00:17:24,502 --> 00:17:27,212
Mr. President, I'm, um...

306
00:17:27,380 --> 00:17:30,006
I don't know what to say. I'm speechless.

307
00:17:30,508 --> 00:17:32,801
All evidence to the contrary.

308
00:17:32,969 --> 00:17:35,137
Mr. President, we haven't met.
I'm Susan Sloan.

309
00:17:35,304 --> 00:17:39,266
I used to work with Congressman Myers.
I hope this incident won't jeopardize...

310
00:17:39,434 --> 00:17:40,517
Sydney?

311
00:17:40,685 --> 00:17:43,019
- Yes, sir.
- You have a second?

312
00:17:43,521 --> 00:17:44,980
Uh, of course.

313
00:17:51,195 --> 00:17:55,198
I thought maybe we might talk in private,
someplace less intimidating.

314
00:17:55,366 --> 00:17:57,159
- Janie.
JANIE: Yes, sir.

315
00:17:57,326 --> 00:18:01,580
This is Janie Basdin, my personal aide.
Show Miss Wade to the rec room, please.

316
00:18:01,748 --> 00:18:03,165
This way.

317
00:18:03,958 --> 00:18:05,917
I'll be with you in a second.

318
00:18:15,428 --> 00:18:19,014
[CLOCK TICKING]

319
00:18:25,897 --> 00:18:27,272
Sorry to keep you waiting.

320
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:30,317
- Mr. President...
- Is it all right if I call you Sydney?

321
00:18:30,735 --> 00:18:32,444
Of course. Mr. President...

322
00:18:32,612 --> 00:18:34,112
Have you ever been in the Oval Office?

323
00:18:34,280 --> 00:18:36,782
Uh, I've just been on the regular tour.
It didn't include...

324
00:18:36,949 --> 00:18:38,742
I hear it's pretty good.

325
00:18:38,910 --> 00:18:41,953
Mr. President, what you saw in there
was vanity run amuck.

326
00:18:42,121 --> 00:18:45,040
I was showing off for a colleague
who doesn't think much of me.

327
00:18:45,208 --> 00:18:49,586
It would be a real injustice to hold the GDC
accountable for my behavior today.

328
00:18:49,754 --> 00:18:54,758
On top of which, I am monumentally sorry
for having insulted you like that.

329
00:18:56,344 --> 00:18:58,428
Are you under the impression
I'm mad at you?

330
00:18:58,596 --> 00:18:59,971
Well, I...

331
00:19:00,139 --> 00:19:02,891
Seldom does a day go by
when I'm not burned in effigy.

332
00:19:03,059 --> 00:19:06,978
Not by a professional political operative
standing 30 feet from the Oval Office.

333
00:19:07,146 --> 00:19:08,855
Now, I'll grant you that.

334
00:19:09,023 --> 00:19:13,151
When the city planners sat down to design
Washington, D.C., their intention was...

335
00:19:13,319 --> 00:19:17,113
...to build a city that would intimidate
and humble foreign heads of state.

336
00:19:17,448 --> 00:19:19,741
- It's true.
- I didn't know that.

337
00:19:20,117 --> 00:19:24,329
The White House is the single greatest
home-court advantage in the modern world.

338
00:19:24,497 --> 00:19:27,040
I learned that one the hard way.

339
00:19:27,250 --> 00:19:29,167
Sydney, this bill is important to me.

340
00:19:29,335 --> 00:19:32,295
Yes, sir. I'll convey your message.

341
00:19:32,463 --> 00:19:33,839
But you don't believe me.

342
00:19:34,006 --> 00:19:36,591
The GDC is asking for 20 percent, sir.

343
00:19:36,759 --> 00:19:39,511
It's not gonna pass at 20 percent.
It's a long shot at 10.

344
00:19:39,679 --> 00:19:42,722
How do you know that,
until you put the White House behind it?

345
00:19:42,890 --> 00:19:44,432
Sydney, at 20 percent...

346
00:19:44,600 --> 00:19:48,311
...we're 34 votes shy in the house.
It can't be done.

347
00:19:48,563 --> 00:19:50,480
But I'll tell you what.

348
00:19:50,940 --> 00:19:52,691
I'll make you a deal.

349
00:19:53,484 --> 00:19:57,696
If you can get 24 votes,
I'll get you the last 10.

350
00:19:57,864 --> 00:19:58,989
Twenty-four votes?

351
00:19:59,156 --> 00:20:01,825
If you can swing 24 votes
by the State of the Union...

352
00:20:01,993 --> 00:20:04,828
...I will promise you
full White House support.

353
00:20:04,996 --> 00:20:07,038
Do I have your word on that, sir?

354
00:20:07,206 --> 00:20:08,957
Absolutely.

355
00:20:10,042 --> 00:20:11,793
Listen, um...

356
00:20:11,961 --> 00:20:13,753
Are you hungry? I skipped breakfast.

357
00:20:13,921 --> 00:20:18,633
You wanna have a doughnut,
coffee or something?

358
00:20:21,804 --> 00:20:24,931
Sir, I'm a little intimidated
by my surroundings and yes...

359
00:20:25,099 --> 00:20:27,726
...I have gotten off
to a rocky and stilted beginning...

360
00:20:27,894 --> 00:20:30,562
...but don't let that diminish
the weight of my message.

361
00:20:30,730 --> 00:20:33,982
The GDC has been at every president
for the last decade and a half...

362
00:20:34,150 --> 00:20:35,984
...that global warming is a calamity...

363
00:20:36,152 --> 00:20:38,904
...the effects of which will be second
only to nuclear war.

364
00:20:39,071 --> 00:20:43,325
The best scientists have given you
every reason to take the GDC seriously...

365
00:20:43,492 --> 00:20:45,118
...but I'm gonna give you one more:

366
00:20:45,286 --> 00:20:48,246
If you don't live up to the deal
you made, come New Hampshire...

367
00:20:48,414 --> 00:20:50,790
...we're gonna go shopping
for a new candidate.

368
00:20:51,208 --> 00:20:52,542
You can't do that, Sydney.

369
00:20:52,710 --> 00:20:55,921
With all due respect, Mr. President,
who's going to stop me?

370
00:20:56,088 --> 00:20:59,549
Well, if you go through that door,
the United States Secret Service.

371
00:20:59,717 --> 00:21:01,051
That's my private office.

372
00:21:02,136 --> 00:21:07,265
- Ah.
- You have to go out that door over there.

373
00:21:19,570 --> 00:21:20,570
[CHUCKLES]

374
00:21:24,075 --> 00:21:27,202
McSorley, McCluskey and Shane know
we're moving on the crime bill.

375
00:21:27,370 --> 00:21:29,329
They're circling the wagons
on assault weapons.

376
00:21:29,497 --> 00:21:30,622
Should I meet with them?

377
00:21:30,790 --> 00:21:33,166
- Let Lewis take a pass at them first.
- Fine.

378
00:21:33,334 --> 00:21:35,502
Two ball in the side.

379
00:21:38,422 --> 00:21:39,839
Nice shot, Mr. President.

380
00:21:40,007 --> 00:21:42,092
"Nice shot, Mr. President"?

381
00:21:42,259 --> 00:21:45,011
You won't even call me by my name
when we're playing pool?

382
00:21:45,179 --> 00:21:47,973
I will not do it playing pool,
I will not do it in a school.

383
00:21:48,140 --> 00:21:51,059
I do not like green eggs and ham,
I do not like them, Sam I am.

384
00:21:51,227 --> 00:21:53,019
At ease, A.J. At ease.

385
00:21:54,855 --> 00:21:57,691
- Would you get away from the pocket?
- I beg your pardon, sir.

386
00:21:57,858 --> 00:22:00,318
Nine ball in the corner.

387
00:22:04,073 --> 00:22:07,742
Solomon phoned. He said he was thrilled
with the deal you made this morning.

388
00:22:08,077 --> 00:22:09,411
I forgot to tell you.

389
00:22:10,371 --> 00:22:12,414
- It's a waste of time.
- But it's not ours.

390
00:22:12,581 --> 00:22:15,583
GDC makes a big push to get the votes.
When they come up short...

391
00:22:15,751 --> 00:22:19,421
...we move in with a softer bill,
get it passed. We're everybody's hero.

392
00:22:19,588 --> 00:22:21,464
Three ball in the side.

393
00:22:21,632 --> 00:22:23,842
Also, Sydney Wade called.

394
00:22:25,720 --> 00:22:26,803
Sydney Wade?

395
00:22:26,971 --> 00:22:30,598
She wanted to apologize one more time
for her behavior.

396
00:22:31,058 --> 00:22:32,726
Excuse me, sir.

397
00:22:32,893 --> 00:22:33,935
[A.J. CLEARS THROAT]

398
00:22:34,103 --> 00:22:35,937
Three in the side.

399
00:22:38,274 --> 00:22:40,191
Did she say anything about me?

400
00:22:40,359 --> 00:22:42,152
- Miss Wade?
- When she called.

401
00:22:42,319 --> 00:22:43,778
Did she say anything about you?

402
00:22:43,946 --> 00:22:48,283
We had a nice couple of minutes together.
She threatened me, I patronized her.

403
00:22:48,451 --> 00:22:51,411
We didn't have anything to eat, but,
uh, I thought there was a connection.

404
00:22:51,579 --> 00:22:53,705
- Hmm, excuse me, sir.
- Sure.

405
00:22:53,873 --> 00:22:55,707
Thirteen in the corner.

406
00:22:57,918 --> 00:22:59,753
She didn't say anything about me?

407
00:22:59,920 --> 00:23:02,756
No, but I could pass her a note
before study hall.

408
00:23:05,926 --> 00:23:08,094
Well, tell me this. Hypothetically...

409
00:23:08,262 --> 00:23:09,679
I feel a nightmare coming on.

410
00:23:09,847 --> 00:23:12,265
What would happen
if I called Sydney Wade...

411
00:23:12,433 --> 00:23:15,977
...and asked her to be my date
at the state dinner on Thursday evening?

412
00:23:17,521 --> 00:23:20,273
- You're not serious.
- Don't I sound serious?

413
00:23:21,025 --> 00:23:25,361
- The president can't just go out on a date.
- Well, why not? Jefferson did. Wilson did.

414
00:23:25,529 --> 00:23:28,990
Wilson was widowed during his first term.
He met a woman, Edith Galt.

415
00:23:29,158 --> 00:23:31,284
He dated her, courted her, married her.

416
00:23:31,452 --> 00:23:34,162
And somewhere in there he managed
to form the League of Nations.

417
00:23:34,330 --> 00:23:37,415
Uh, Mr. President,
this is an election year.

418
00:23:37,583 --> 00:23:39,626
If you're looking
for female companionship...

419
00:23:39,794 --> 00:23:42,587
...we can make arrangements
that will ensure total privacy.

420
00:23:42,755 --> 00:23:45,298
I don't want you to get me a girl.
What is this, Vegas?

421
00:23:45,591 --> 00:23:47,133
No, sir. This is the White House.

422
00:23:47,301 --> 00:23:50,720
I'm talking about something
that is not a conflict with my oath of office.

423
00:23:50,888 --> 00:23:54,140
I'm a single adult. I met a woman
who I'd like to see again socially.

424
00:23:54,308 --> 00:23:56,309
How is that different
from what Wilson did?

425
00:23:56,477 --> 00:23:59,395
The difference is he didn't have to be
president on television.

426
00:23:59,563 --> 00:24:01,272
You said it yourself a million times:

427
00:24:01,440 --> 00:24:04,400
If there had been a TV
in every living room 60 years ago...

428
00:24:04,568 --> 00:24:07,320
...this country does not elect a man
in a wheelchair.

429
00:24:08,155 --> 00:24:10,031
So what are you saying?

430
00:24:10,199 --> 00:24:12,867
- I'm saying we'll take a hit.
- How big?

431
00:24:13,327 --> 00:24:15,286
I don't know. Five points, maybe more.

432
00:24:15,788 --> 00:24:18,832
- We're talking here about five points?
- Could be more.

433
00:24:18,999 --> 00:24:22,085
I'd drop five points if Wisconsin
doesn't make it to the Rose Bowl.

434
00:24:22,253 --> 00:24:24,212
Five ball in the corner.

435
00:24:25,256 --> 00:24:28,341
Want me to have Kodak put together
some numbers so we know?

436
00:24:28,509 --> 00:24:29,676
Yeah. Yeah.

437
00:24:29,844 --> 00:24:32,804
No. I don't want a checkup polling sample
to see if it's okay...

438
00:24:32,972 --> 00:24:36,349
...like I'm asking permission
to stay out an hour past curfew.

439
00:24:36,517 --> 00:24:39,018
This is not the business
of the American people.

440
00:24:39,436 --> 00:24:40,770
With all due respect, sir...

441
00:24:40,938 --> 00:24:44,774
...Americans have a funny way of deciding
what is and what is not their business.

442
00:24:47,319 --> 00:24:49,154
I like her, A.J.

443
00:24:53,284 --> 00:24:56,327
Stop being my chief of staff
for one minute.

444
00:24:58,205 --> 00:24:59,414
Give her a call.

445
00:25:00,499 --> 00:25:01,749
Janie!

446
00:25:03,377 --> 00:25:05,170
She didn't say anything about me?

447
00:25:05,337 --> 00:25:08,756
Uh, she did say you were taller
than she thought you'd be.

448
00:25:09,175 --> 00:25:10,175
Well, that's something.

449
00:25:10,342 --> 00:25:12,218
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

450
00:25:12,386 --> 00:25:13,511
Yes, sir.

451
00:25:13,679 --> 00:25:16,347
Janie, I need you to track down
a phone number for me.

452
00:25:18,309 --> 00:25:20,602
SYDNEY:
Richard, Richard...

453
00:25:20,769 --> 00:25:22,312
It wasn't funny.

454
00:25:22,479 --> 00:25:25,273
I acted like a college freshman
at a protest rally.

455
00:25:25,441 --> 00:25:27,650
Tell him about
walking out the wrong door.

456
00:25:27,818 --> 00:25:30,320
Oh, God. I forgot about that.

457
00:25:30,487 --> 00:25:34,449
No, Richard, no. No, I don't want to hear
your Andrew Shepherd imitation.

458
00:25:34,617 --> 00:25:35,617
I want to hear it.

459
00:25:35,784 --> 00:25:37,368
I'm hanging up now, Richard.

460
00:25:37,536 --> 00:25:40,997
Uh, tonight I was gonna go to bed early
and wake up when there's a new president.

461
00:25:41,165 --> 00:25:42,832
[CHUCKLES]

462
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:45,877
Pssh, the president must think
I'm a third-rate jerk.

463
00:25:46,045 --> 00:25:49,047
If he thinks you're a jerk,
he thinks you're a first-rate jerk.

464
00:25:49,215 --> 00:25:51,841
I'll tell you one thing, boy. I regrouped.

465
00:25:52,009 --> 00:25:54,761
You gotta give me that.
I pulled it together at the end.

466
00:25:54,929 --> 00:25:58,556
I stood in the middle of the Oval Office
and made it clear that from now on...

467
00:25:58,724 --> 00:26:01,809
...he who doesn't take the GDC seriously,
does so at his peril.

468
00:26:01,977 --> 00:26:03,728
And then you walked out
the wrong door.

469
00:26:03,896 --> 00:26:06,272
You gonna throw that at me
the rest of my life?

470
00:26:06,565 --> 00:26:08,107
That's my current plan, yes.

471
00:26:08,275 --> 00:26:09,442
[PHONE RINGS]

472
00:26:09,610 --> 00:26:12,403
Oh, that's gonna be Leo Solomon.
He said he'd call at 9.

473
00:26:12,571 --> 00:26:14,113
- Hello?
SHEPHERD [OVER PHONE]: Yeah, hi.

474
00:26:14,281 --> 00:26:15,365
Is this Sydney?

475
00:26:15,532 --> 00:26:18,618
- Leo?
- No, this is Andrew Shepherd.

476
00:26:18,786 --> 00:26:20,411
Oh, it's Andrew Shepherd.

477
00:26:20,579 --> 00:26:24,290
Yeah, you're hilarious, Richard.
You're just a regular riot.

478
00:26:24,583 --> 00:26:27,543
No, this isn't Richard.
This is Andrew Shepherd.

479
00:26:27,711 --> 00:26:29,254
Ah, well, I'm so glad you called...

480
00:26:29,421 --> 00:26:32,799
...because I forgot to tell you today
what a nice ass you have.

481
00:26:32,967 --> 00:26:37,679
I'm also impressed that you got my number,
given the fact that I don't have a phone.

482
00:26:37,846 --> 00:26:39,889
- Good night, Richard.
- Uh, this isn't Rich...

483
00:26:40,057 --> 00:26:41,432
[LINE DISCONNECTS]

484
00:26:42,810 --> 00:26:45,436
This used to be easier.

485
00:26:47,439 --> 00:26:49,607
[PHONE RINGING]

486
00:26:49,775 --> 00:26:52,277
- I can't believe this.
- You want me to deal with him?

487
00:26:52,444 --> 00:26:57,156
No way. I may choke in front of Shepherd.
Richard Reynolds, I can handle. Hello?

488
00:26:57,908 --> 00:26:58,950
Sydney?

489
00:26:59,118 --> 00:27:00,368
Are you learning-impaired?

490
00:27:00,536 --> 00:27:03,121
Listen, do me a favor. Hang up the phone.

491
00:27:03,622 --> 00:27:04,664
What?

492
00:27:04,832 --> 00:27:09,168
Hang up the phone, then dial 456-1414.

493
00:27:09,336 --> 00:27:11,170
When you get
the White House operator...

494
00:27:11,338 --> 00:27:15,174
...give her your name and tell her
you want to speak to the president.

495
00:27:20,180 --> 00:27:21,806
Oh, my God.

496
00:27:21,974 --> 00:27:23,850
This isn't happening to me.

497
00:27:24,018 --> 00:27:25,101
What's going on?

498
00:27:25,477 --> 00:27:29,022
No, it's not possible
I did this twice in one day.

499
00:27:29,189 --> 00:27:30,773
[SIGHS]

500
00:27:35,612 --> 00:27:37,780
WOMAN [OVER PHONE]:
Good evening, the White House.

501
00:27:38,324 --> 00:27:39,615
- Hello?
- Hi.

502
00:27:39,783 --> 00:27:42,035
My name's Sydney Ellen Wade.
I'd like to...

503
00:27:42,202 --> 00:27:45,038
The president's expecting your call, ma'am.
I'll put you right through.

504
00:27:45,205 --> 00:27:48,499
[LINE BEEPS THEN RINGS]

505
00:27:48,667 --> 00:27:49,792
SHEPHERD [OVER PHONE]:
Hello?

506
00:27:49,960 --> 00:27:51,919
Mr. President, heh, um...

507
00:27:52,087 --> 00:27:56,215
Uh... Uh, I'm sure there's an appropriate
thing to say at this moment, uh...

508
00:27:56,383 --> 00:28:01,262
Probably some formal apology for
the "nice ass" remark would be in order.

509
00:28:01,513 --> 00:28:03,097
I don't quite know how to word it.

510
00:28:03,349 --> 00:28:05,683
It's my fault.
I shouldn't have called you at home.

511
00:28:05,851 --> 00:28:09,145
- Should I call you at the office tomorrow?
- No, no. Of course not.

512
00:28:09,355 --> 00:28:13,274
I mean, yes. You can call me
any time you want. This is fine, right now.

513
00:28:13,442 --> 00:28:15,818
When I said "of course not," I meant...

514
00:28:15,986 --> 00:28:18,863
Know what? The hell with it.
I'm moving to another country.

515
00:28:19,156 --> 00:28:21,783
What did you mean when you said
you didn't have a phone?

516
00:28:21,950 --> 00:28:25,536
Oh, I just moved here over the weekend
and my apartment isn't ready yet.

517
00:28:25,704 --> 00:28:29,749
This is my sister's apartment. Come to
think of it, how did you get this number?

518
00:28:29,917 --> 00:28:32,085
How did I get the number?
That's a good question.

519
00:28:32,252 --> 00:28:35,338
Um, I don't know. Probably the FBI.

520
00:28:35,506 --> 00:28:37,298
Oh, the FBI. Sure.

521
00:28:37,466 --> 00:28:41,469
Because if you want to find someone, and
you're the president, that's who you'd call.

522
00:28:41,720 --> 00:28:43,054
You know who else is good at that?

523
00:28:43,222 --> 00:28:45,848
Uh, CIA?

524
00:28:46,016 --> 00:28:48,393
I was thinking
of the Internal Revenue Service.

525
00:28:48,560 --> 00:28:51,687
They have these computer files
that, uh...

526
00:28:51,855 --> 00:28:54,065
Well, I, ahem, should stop stalling.

527
00:28:54,233 --> 00:28:59,320
Um, as you probably know, the French
have elected themselves a new president.

528
00:28:59,488 --> 00:29:02,990
We're having a formal state dinner
at the White House and I was wondering...

529
00:29:03,158 --> 00:29:06,661
...and, uh, you're under no obligation
of law, but I thought it might be fun.

530
00:29:06,829 --> 00:29:09,705
I was wondering
if maybe you wanted to go...

531
00:29:09,873 --> 00:29:12,333
...with me and, um...

532
00:29:12,501 --> 00:29:15,670
Well, that's it. That's why I was calling.

533
00:29:21,635 --> 00:29:23,136
Sydney?

534
00:29:24,221 --> 00:29:27,223
- Sydney, Congress doesn't take this long.
- Mr. President...

535
00:29:27,766 --> 00:29:29,559
[CHUCKLES]

536
00:29:29,726 --> 00:29:34,230
You have asked me to join you
in representing our country.

537
00:29:34,398 --> 00:29:38,985
I'm honored. I'm equal to the task.
I won't let you down, sir.

538
00:29:39,778 --> 00:29:43,573
This is just dinner. We're not going
to be doing espionage or anything.

539
00:29:43,740 --> 00:29:45,616
No, of course, ha, ha.

540
00:29:45,784 --> 00:29:48,703
I'm a little, um... Uh...

541
00:29:48,871 --> 00:29:51,038
What do I do? Ha-ha-ha!

542
00:29:51,206 --> 00:29:55,293
I mean, you know, where do I go?
I mean, will you meet me?

543
00:29:56,086 --> 00:29:59,505
I'm gonna have a very nice woman
named Marsha Bridgeport call you.

544
00:29:59,673 --> 00:30:01,591
She's the White House social secretary.

545
00:30:01,758 --> 00:30:04,218
She's gonna help you
with anything you want.

546
00:30:04,386 --> 00:30:07,847
Now, when she calls you and tells you
her name is Marsha Bridgeport...

547
00:30:08,015 --> 00:30:10,475
...it'll help if you give her
the benefit of the doubt.

548
00:30:10,642 --> 00:30:11,893
[CHUCKLES]

549
00:30:12,060 --> 00:30:15,396
- Of course.
- And I'll see you Thursday night.

550
00:30:15,689 --> 00:30:19,358
Mr. President,
thanks for asking me, really.

551
00:30:19,526 --> 00:30:23,029
- This is a first for me.
- Me too.

552
00:30:29,369 --> 00:30:32,955
Okay, who's on Indiana? New people?
I can't remember your names.

553
00:30:33,123 --> 00:30:37,168
Raise your hands if you're on Indiana.
Put your hands down. You're on Illinois.

554
00:30:37,336 --> 00:30:39,295
- We got Jarrett.
- What?

555
00:30:39,755 --> 00:30:42,340
George Jarrett. He's ours, solid "yes."

556
00:30:42,508 --> 00:30:44,717
I don't believe it. You, new guy...

557
00:30:44,885 --> 00:30:48,930
Jarrett, Democrat, Minnesota,
slide his name on over to "yes."

558
00:30:49,473 --> 00:30:53,267
He was undecided. How did you get
the fence pole out of his butt?

559
00:30:53,435 --> 00:30:57,104
Wish I could take credit. He says,
"Lewis, I support the president 100 percent.

560
00:30:57,272 --> 00:30:58,773
Not the bill, the president."

561
00:30:58,941 --> 00:31:02,026
We're gonna win this.
It's like a kissing booth at a carnival:

562
00:31:02,194 --> 00:31:04,779
Give us a vote, get a photo op
with number 63.

563
00:31:04,947 --> 00:31:08,241
- We should've gone after the handguns.
- One thing at a time.

564
00:31:08,450 --> 00:31:10,493
We don't have time
to do one thing at a time.

565
00:31:12,162 --> 00:31:14,622
DAVID: Yeah, hi.
It's David in Sydney Wade's office.

566
00:31:14,790 --> 00:31:16,415
Yeah, I'll hold.

567
00:31:17,334 --> 00:31:20,962
I'm from Sydney Wade's office. I wanna
confirm her lunch with the congressman.

568
00:31:21,129 --> 00:31:23,673
We can do with a little party leadership.

569
00:31:24,883 --> 00:31:27,927
I mean, is the Majority Whip
taking a break?

570
00:31:28,095 --> 00:31:31,013
Congress is in session, right?
I'm not wrong about that.

571
00:31:31,181 --> 00:31:32,974
I just got off with Luther Simons.

572
00:31:33,141 --> 00:31:35,226
- Brock's on board.
DAVID: Terrific.

573
00:31:35,394 --> 00:31:37,812
All right, well, have him get back to me.

574
00:31:40,357 --> 00:31:41,899
You okay, Syd?

575
00:31:42,776 --> 00:31:43,818
Sure, why?

576
00:31:43,986 --> 00:31:46,237
I don't know. You seem a little tense.

577
00:31:46,405 --> 00:31:48,197
What do you mean?

578
00:31:51,827 --> 00:31:54,954
What do you have, big date tonight?

579
00:32:08,719 --> 00:32:10,928
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

580
00:32:16,435 --> 00:32:19,729
Senator, Senator Rumson,
if I can have a moment with you, sir.

581
00:32:19,896 --> 00:32:20,896
Certainly.

582
00:32:21,064 --> 00:32:23,816
I'm standing here with
Senate Minority Leader Robert Rumson...

583
00:32:23,984 --> 00:32:27,153
...one of the many guests arriving at what,
for the next few hours...

584
00:32:27,321 --> 00:32:29,113
...will be a nonpartisan White House.

585
00:32:29,573 --> 00:32:32,867
Senator, the latest public-opinion surveys
show the president...

586
00:32:33,035 --> 00:32:36,954
...with approval ratings that would make him
all but unbeatable come next November.

587
00:32:37,122 --> 00:32:39,790
Is there a Republican who can mount
a serious challenge...

588
00:32:39,958 --> 00:32:41,375
...and are you that candidate?

589
00:32:41,543 --> 00:32:45,880
It's a long time till November. Right now
I'm looking forward to a pleasant evening.

590
00:32:46,048 --> 00:32:47,089
Thank you, senator.

591
00:32:49,009 --> 00:32:51,010
That's a little tight, Luce.

592
00:32:51,178 --> 00:32:54,388
It's supposed to be.
It's supposed to make you look regal.

593
00:32:54,556 --> 00:32:57,475
Is it supposed to cut off
the blood flow to my face?

594
00:32:59,519 --> 00:33:00,895
All done.

595
00:33:05,275 --> 00:33:08,444
Well, that's not bad.
Where'd you learn how to do that?

596
00:33:08,612 --> 00:33:09,737
Social studies.

597
00:33:09,905 --> 00:33:12,281
Very funny. No, really,
where'd you learn that?

598
00:33:12,866 --> 00:33:15,785
I don't know. I just...
Guess I picked it up somewhere.

599
00:33:17,037 --> 00:33:19,622
Sweetie, did Mom teach you
how to do that?

600
00:33:20,457 --> 00:33:21,957
Yeah.

601
00:33:24,503 --> 00:33:28,798
Lucy, is this okay,
my having dinner with a lady?

602
00:33:28,965 --> 00:33:30,132
Dad, it's totally okay.

603
00:33:30,300 --> 00:33:32,802
You sure? Because if there's anything
you want to talk about...

604
00:33:32,969 --> 00:33:36,472
Dad. It's cool. Just go for it.

605
00:33:36,640 --> 00:33:38,099
Okay.

606
00:33:39,643 --> 00:33:40,643
[SIGHS]

607
00:33:40,811 --> 00:33:42,019
You know, I'm a little nervous.

608
00:33:42,187 --> 00:33:44,021
You'll be fine. Just be yourself.

609
00:33:44,564 --> 00:33:46,023
Be myself?

610
00:33:46,191 --> 00:33:49,151
Yeah, and, um, compliment her shoes.

611
00:33:49,695 --> 00:33:50,903
Her shoes?

612
00:33:51,405 --> 00:33:53,614
Yeah. Girls like that.

613
00:33:54,991 --> 00:33:57,535
Okay. Thanks.

614
00:34:08,422 --> 00:34:09,630
- Thank you.
- Miss Wade?

615
00:34:09,798 --> 00:34:10,923
- Oh, hi.
- Good evening.

616
00:34:11,091 --> 00:34:13,843
The president would like you
to join him in the residence.

617
00:34:14,010 --> 00:34:16,679
- May I show you the way?
- Of course.

618
00:34:17,973 --> 00:34:20,099
[SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

619
00:34:26,523 --> 00:34:29,358
[PEOPLE LAUGHING]

620
00:34:29,526 --> 00:34:32,069
Sydney, come on in. You look beautiful.

621
00:34:32,237 --> 00:34:34,321
Thanks.
I have no idea what I'm doing here.

622
00:34:34,489 --> 00:34:36,323
- I promise you, there's no hidden agenda.
- Heh.

623
00:34:36,491 --> 00:34:37,700
You know my wife, Esther.

624
00:34:37,868 --> 00:34:40,619
- Nice to see you again.
- Sydney.

625
00:34:41,246 --> 00:34:43,289
Andrew Shepherd.
We spoke on the phone.

626
00:34:43,457 --> 00:34:45,708
Yes, sir. I remember.

627
00:34:45,876 --> 00:34:47,418
- Excuse me one minute.
A. J: Ha, ha.

628
00:34:47,586 --> 00:34:51,756
The president told me how you two met,
Sydney. I think it's priceless.

629
00:34:51,923 --> 00:34:55,801
One minute I was calling him
a mockery of an environmental leader...

630
00:34:55,969 --> 00:34:57,678
...the next minute I had a date.

631
00:34:57,846 --> 00:35:01,223
Men like being insulted by women.
It makes them feel loved.

632
00:35:01,391 --> 00:35:02,516
Don't ask me why.

633
00:35:02,684 --> 00:35:05,644
Mr. President, allow me
to introduce to you Sydney Ellen Wade...

634
00:35:05,812 --> 00:35:07,480
...of the Commonwealth of Virginia.

635
00:35:07,856 --> 00:35:10,399
This is President René Jean D'Astier and...

636
00:35:10,567 --> 00:35:13,068
...his wife, Monique Danielle D'Astier,
of France.

637
00:35:13,236 --> 00:35:16,447
- It's a great pleasure to meet you.
- It's an honor to meet you both.

638
00:35:16,615 --> 00:35:18,199
I'm so pleased to meet you.

639
00:35:18,366 --> 00:35:22,161
Ahem, Mr. President, I'm sorry to interrupt.
The receiving line is in place.

640
00:35:22,329 --> 00:35:25,164
Sydney, I think our table's ready.

641
00:35:32,547 --> 00:35:36,175
I've got to do a thing at the bottom
of the stairs, but you'll be escorted...

642
00:35:36,343 --> 00:35:38,427
- They took me through it.
- Oh, good.

643
00:35:38,595 --> 00:35:41,013
Do you do this often, sir?

644
00:35:41,181 --> 00:35:43,557
This is actually
only our second state dinner.

645
00:35:43,725 --> 00:35:46,143
The first one was
for the Emperor of Japan...

646
00:35:46,311 --> 00:35:49,563
...who died shortly after,
so we stopped having them, just in case.

647
00:35:49,731 --> 00:35:52,358
I meant do you go out on, uh...
Do you often...

648
00:35:52,526 --> 00:35:53,943
- Do I date a lot?
- Yeah.

649
00:35:54,110 --> 00:35:55,528
No, how about you?

650
00:35:55,695 --> 00:35:59,698
Me? Well, lately I seem to be going out
on a lot of first dates.

651
00:35:59,866 --> 00:36:02,743
- You're experienced at this.
- You could ask me anything.

652
00:36:02,911 --> 00:36:04,161
How are we doing so far?

653
00:36:04,329 --> 00:36:08,916
It's hard to say at this point.
So far it's just your typical first-date stuff.

654
00:36:09,334 --> 00:36:11,627
Damn, I wanted to be different
from the others.

655
00:36:11,795 --> 00:36:15,089
MAN: Ladies and gentlemen,
the president of the United States.

656
00:36:15,257 --> 00:36:16,298
By the way...

657
00:36:16,466 --> 00:36:17,883
MAN: Accompanied by...
- Nice shoes.

658
00:36:18,051 --> 00:36:21,387
MAN: The president of France
and Madame D'Astier.

659
00:36:21,555 --> 00:36:25,224
[BAND PLAYING "HAIL TO THE CHIEF"]

660
00:36:30,480 --> 00:36:33,649
[JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING INDISTINCTLY]

661
00:36:33,817 --> 00:36:37,278
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

662
00:36:42,409 --> 00:36:44,785
[ALL SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

663
00:36:56,840 --> 00:36:58,173
- Mr. President?
- Yeah?

664
00:36:58,341 --> 00:37:00,885
The president and Mrs. D'Astier look bored.

665
00:37:01,720 --> 00:37:03,804
They're not talking to anybody.

666
00:37:05,682 --> 00:37:07,391
- They're hammered.
- Ha, ha.

667
00:37:07,559 --> 00:37:10,185
- Esther, do you speak French?
- Latin.

668
00:37:10,353 --> 00:37:12,813
- I thought you spoke French.
- No, Latin.

669
00:37:12,981 --> 00:37:15,357
Great. Next time Julius Caesar
comes to town, you're our gal.

670
00:37:15,525 --> 00:37:17,151
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

671
00:37:17,319 --> 00:37:18,861
Sydney, I don't suppose that...

672
00:37:19,029 --> 00:37:21,030
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

673
00:37:28,038 --> 00:37:29,204
That's my date.

674
00:37:29,372 --> 00:37:31,373
[SPEAKING IN FRENCH]

675
00:37:41,009 --> 00:37:42,009
[IN ENGLISH]
Really?

676
00:37:42,177 --> 00:37:43,844
[SPEAKS IN FRENCH]

677
00:37:44,012 --> 00:37:46,430
You didn't dissolve our trade agreements,
did you? Heh.

678
00:37:46,598 --> 00:37:49,600
Heh, no. I just said we're sitting
in this beautiful room...

679
00:37:49,768 --> 00:37:52,353
...listening to the music
of this wonderful orchestra...

680
00:37:52,520 --> 00:37:54,521
...and I wondered
why nobody was dancing.

681
00:37:54,689 --> 00:37:56,732
[IN ENGLISH]
I told Miss Wade that, in my country...

682
00:37:56,900 --> 00:38:00,194
...a guest of the palace
of Louis XVI and Marie Antoinette...

683
00:38:00,362 --> 00:38:02,529
...would soon find their head
in a guillotine...

684
00:38:02,697 --> 00:38:05,324
...if they made the impertinent gesture
of dancing...

685
00:38:05,492 --> 00:38:08,702
...without so much as a by-your-leave
from the king and the queen.

686
00:38:08,870 --> 00:38:10,329
[LAUGHS]

687
00:38:10,497 --> 00:38:12,456
I bet no one accused Louis
of being soft on crime.

688
00:38:12,624 --> 00:38:14,041
[ALL LAUGHING]

689
00:38:14,417 --> 00:38:18,003
- There's a lesson there, Mr. President.
- More beheadings at the White House.

690
00:38:18,171 --> 00:38:20,089
Bob Rumson would embrace it.

691
00:38:20,256 --> 00:38:22,424
Yes, I'm sure he would.

692
00:38:23,593 --> 00:38:25,427
I have a better idea.

693
00:38:29,599 --> 00:38:31,225
Would you like to dance?

694
00:38:31,935 --> 00:38:33,018
Ah.

695
00:38:33,186 --> 00:38:34,853
Yeah, I guess.

696
00:38:35,021 --> 00:38:37,231
I mean, yes, sir...

697
00:38:37,399 --> 00:38:39,108
...I'd love to.

698
00:38:55,709 --> 00:38:57,418
They're dancing.

699
00:39:12,934 --> 00:39:14,226
[SIGHS]

700
00:39:14,394 --> 00:39:16,812
[IN LOW VOICE]
I don't know how you do it.

701
00:39:17,272 --> 00:39:20,024
- It's Arthur Murray. Six lessons.
- Ha-ha-ha.

702
00:39:20,233 --> 00:39:21,984
That's not what I mean.

703
00:39:22,652 --> 00:39:27,364
Two hundred pairs of eyes are focused
on you right now with two questions:

704
00:39:27,532 --> 00:39:31,410
"Who's this girl?" and,
"Why is the president dancing with her?"

705
00:39:31,578 --> 00:39:36,040
Well, first of all, the 200 pairs of eyes
are not focused on me.

706
00:39:36,207 --> 00:39:38,500
They're focused on you.

707
00:39:38,960 --> 00:39:41,920
And the answers are,
"Sydney Ellen Wade.

708
00:39:42,088 --> 00:39:44,465
Because she said 'yes."'

709
00:40:06,988 --> 00:40:08,864
[SIGHS]

710
00:40:17,207 --> 00:40:19,708
MAN 1: Does the setup here work?
MAN 2: How's it going?

711
00:40:24,798 --> 00:40:27,424
- Good morning, Mrs. Chapil.
CHAPIL: Morning, Mr. President.

712
00:40:27,592 --> 00:40:29,885
Mr. Rothschild and Miss McCall
are in the office.

713
00:40:30,428 --> 00:40:32,346
They said they need to speak with you.

714
00:40:32,514 --> 00:40:34,890
Janie, can you get me the number
of a local florist?

715
00:40:35,058 --> 00:40:36,642
Where do you want them sent?

716
00:40:36,810 --> 00:40:39,812
No, I want to do it myself.
I just need the number.

717
00:40:40,396 --> 00:40:41,438
I don't understand.

718
00:40:44,400 --> 00:40:47,194
I want the phone number of a florist.

719
00:40:47,362 --> 00:40:49,279
You just want the phone number.

720
00:40:50,365 --> 00:40:51,615
Yeah.

721
00:40:52,325 --> 00:40:54,535
- Sir, is there a problem...
- I want to send some flowers.

722
00:40:54,702 --> 00:40:58,539
I want to do it myself. I don't want
to staff it out. No executive orders.

723
00:40:58,706 --> 00:41:00,457
I just want a phone number.

724
00:41:01,251 --> 00:41:03,877
I'll get it for you right away, sir.

725
00:41:04,629 --> 00:41:06,171
- Morning.
ROBIN: Good morning.

726
00:41:06,339 --> 00:41:07,840
We need five minutes of your time.

727
00:41:08,007 --> 00:41:09,633
SHEPHERD:
I'll be with you in two minutes.

728
00:41:09,801 --> 00:41:11,260
I just need to make a call.

729
00:41:11,511 --> 00:41:12,845
Thank you, Janie.

730
00:41:17,767 --> 00:41:19,059
Who are we calling, sir?

731
00:41:19,894 --> 00:41:23,647
The Organization of United Brotherhood
of It's None of Your Damn Business.

732
00:41:23,815 --> 00:41:26,316
- I'll be with you in a second.
- Yes, sir.

733
00:41:28,736 --> 00:41:30,571
[SIGHS]

734
00:41:32,407 --> 00:41:33,949
Yeah, hi, good morning.

735
00:41:34,117 --> 00:41:35,951
How do I get an outside line?

736
00:41:36,119 --> 00:41:37,202
[DIALTONE]

737
00:41:37,370 --> 00:41:39,371
Well, that was simple.

738
00:41:41,875 --> 00:41:44,042
- Janie?
- Yes.

739
00:41:44,210 --> 00:41:46,336
What's the president doing?

740
00:41:46,504 --> 00:41:50,215
I'm sorry, I'm really not at liberty to say.

741
00:41:50,717 --> 00:41:54,469
Yes, hi, good morning.
Is this Carmen's House of Flowers?

742
00:41:54,637 --> 00:41:57,764
Good. I'd like to order
some flowers, please.

743
00:41:59,184 --> 00:42:02,060
Well, tell me,
what is the state flower of Virginia?

744
00:42:02,562 --> 00:42:05,230
Does this have something to do
with Sydney Wade?

745
00:42:05,398 --> 00:42:08,192
I'm really not at liberty to say.

746
00:42:08,359 --> 00:42:11,069
Well, is there anybody there
who might know?

747
00:42:12,030 --> 00:42:14,990
No, I'm not trying to be difficult.
Uh...

748
00:42:15,158 --> 00:42:16,909
Hang on, please.

749
00:42:18,286 --> 00:42:20,746
Janie, what is the state flower
of Virginia?

750
00:42:20,914 --> 00:42:24,124
- Mrs. Chapil, state flower of Virginia?
- The dogwood.

751
00:42:24,834 --> 00:42:26,877
The dogwood, sir.

752
00:42:27,045 --> 00:42:28,462
Thank you.

753
00:42:29,672 --> 00:42:31,465
It's a dogwood.

754
00:42:32,592 --> 00:42:34,051
Really?

755
00:42:34,594 --> 00:42:37,137
Ah, hold on, please. Ahem.

756
00:42:37,305 --> 00:42:40,224
Janie, the dogwood's a tree,
it's not a flower.

757
00:42:40,391 --> 00:42:42,351
Actually, it's a tree and a flower.

758
00:42:42,518 --> 00:42:44,394
- Are you sure?
- Yes. What's going on?

759
00:42:44,854 --> 00:42:47,397
JANIE:
Sir, it's a tree and a flower.

760
00:42:49,400 --> 00:42:53,445
The dogwood is a tree and a flower.
I'd like a dozen, please.

761
00:42:54,364 --> 00:42:56,114
Really, no dogwoods?

762
00:42:56,282 --> 00:42:57,282
[SIGHS]

763
00:42:57,450 --> 00:42:59,409
How about, uh, roses?

764
00:42:59,577 --> 00:43:02,037
Simple, classic. Two dozen?

765
00:43:02,205 --> 00:43:03,372
Janie...

766
00:43:03,539 --> 00:43:07,417
I'm the president's senior domestic
policy advisor. Now, it's important...

767
00:43:07,585 --> 00:43:10,379
SHEPHERD: Janie, do you know
where my credit cards are?

768
00:43:12,257 --> 00:43:14,549
They're in storage in Wisconsin
with the rest...

769
00:43:14,717 --> 00:43:17,552
...of your personal items.
- All right.

770
00:43:17,720 --> 00:43:22,849
Perhaps it would be better if you bill me.
I'm sure it'll be all right with your boss.

771
00:43:23,810 --> 00:43:28,063
I don't know if you recognize my voice,
but, uh, this is the president.

772
00:43:28,898 --> 00:43:30,732
Of the United States.

773
00:43:32,277 --> 00:43:34,903
Hello?

774
00:43:36,072 --> 00:43:38,282
Leo, you wanted to see me?

775
00:43:38,449 --> 00:43:39,992
So there I was thinking:

776
00:43:40,159 --> 00:43:41,743
Maybe I should give Sydney a call.

777
00:43:41,911 --> 00:43:44,037
She's new in town,
doesn't know many people.

778
00:43:44,205 --> 00:43:45,497
Then I picked up the Times.

779
00:43:45,957 --> 00:43:49,167
Leo, it was crazy. He called me at home.

780
00:43:49,502 --> 00:43:51,420
- What's going on?
- Nothing.

781
00:43:51,587 --> 00:43:55,090
It was innocent.
His cousin got the flu at the last minute.

782
00:43:55,258 --> 00:43:57,342
- Did you sleep with him?
- Leo.

783
00:43:57,510 --> 00:44:00,470
- Did you sleep with him?
- That's none of your business, Leo.

784
00:44:00,680 --> 00:44:04,141
- Yeah, it is, Sydney.
- You wanna tell me how my personal life...

785
00:44:04,309 --> 00:44:06,768
Because when it's the president,
it's not personal.

786
00:44:06,936 --> 00:44:10,772
I hired your reputation, Sydney.
I hired a pit bull, not a prom queen.

787
00:44:10,940 --> 00:44:14,735
- That's unfair.
- It's incredibly unfair.

788
00:44:14,902 --> 00:44:18,780
You spent time over the years telling me
the trouble with the environmental lobby...

789
00:44:18,948 --> 00:44:21,116
...is that we don't understand
the fundamental truth...

790
00:44:21,284 --> 00:44:22,951
...that politics is perception.

791
00:44:23,119 --> 00:44:24,953
This is a bad time to develop ignorance.

792
00:44:25,121 --> 00:44:27,372
- You're making way too much of this.
- Am I?

793
00:44:28,124 --> 00:44:32,085
This is your time, Sydney.
You're sitting at the grown-up's table.

794
00:44:32,253 --> 00:44:34,504
You have a chance to get
everything you want:

795
00:44:34,672 --> 00:44:38,717
Run a national campaign,
be a major player inside the party.

796
00:44:39,385 --> 00:44:41,345
This relationship
better go all the way...

797
00:44:41,512 --> 00:44:45,057
...because with the leader of the free world,
there's no halfway.

798
00:44:45,350 --> 00:44:47,184
Politics is perception...

799
00:44:47,352 --> 00:44:48,935
...and if this doesn't work out...

800
00:44:49,103 --> 00:44:51,605
...the time it'll take
to go from being a hired gun...

801
00:44:51,773 --> 00:44:54,274
...to a cocktail-party joke
can be clocked with an egg timer.

802
00:44:54,442 --> 00:44:58,612
Leo, there's no relationship.
It was one night. It's done.

803
00:44:58,821 --> 00:45:01,782
Mr. Solomon, this was just delivered
by a White House messenger.

804
00:45:01,949 --> 00:45:03,116
It's marked "perishable."

805
00:45:03,451 --> 00:45:05,494
The White House sent me
something perishable?

806
00:45:05,661 --> 00:45:07,079
It's for Miss Wade.

807
00:45:07,246 --> 00:45:11,124
- Here we go.
- Relax, Leo, I'm sure it's just a formality.

808
00:45:11,292 --> 00:45:13,377
- It's from him.
- Of course it's from him.

809
00:45:13,544 --> 00:45:16,296
So he had some staff flunky
send me a fruit basket.

810
00:45:16,464 --> 00:45:19,758
- Well, he wrote the note himself.
- I'm sure he didn't take the time...

811
00:45:19,926 --> 00:45:23,512
The messenger waited 10 minutes
while the president wrote the card.

812
00:45:23,846 --> 00:45:26,056
Okay, listen...

813
00:45:26,849 --> 00:45:31,436
- It took him 10 minutes to write the card?
- Apparently, he went through several drafts.

814
00:45:36,818 --> 00:45:38,777
[CHUCKLES]

815
00:45:45,827 --> 00:45:46,993
[LAUGHS]

816
00:45:47,161 --> 00:45:48,245
What is it?

817
00:45:48,746 --> 00:45:49,955
- A ham.
- A ham?

818
00:45:50,123 --> 00:45:51,206
[LAUGHS]

819
00:45:51,374 --> 00:45:54,126
He sent me a Virginia ham.

820
00:45:54,293 --> 00:45:57,045
Dig it, Miss Wade,
you're the president's girlfriend.

821
00:45:58,297 --> 00:46:01,007
There's never an egg timer around
when you need one.

822
00:46:05,513 --> 00:46:06,888
Thanks.

823
00:46:09,767 --> 00:46:11,101
ROBIN:
They'll be pressing today...

824
00:46:11,269 --> 00:46:14,563
...if we're prepared to soften
the assault weapons section of the bill.

825
00:46:14,730 --> 00:46:17,315
There's no need to entertain that
at this point.

826
00:46:19,735 --> 00:46:22,404
How do you want me to handle
the Sydney issue?

827
00:46:23,739 --> 00:46:25,699
"The Sydney issue"?

828
00:46:25,867 --> 00:46:28,952
We should have a consensus
on how the White House will handle it.

829
00:46:29,120 --> 00:46:33,748
I certainly hope "the Sydney issue" refers
to a problem we're having with Australia.

830
00:46:33,916 --> 00:46:36,501
- If it's anything other than that...
JANIE: Ahem, Mr. President...

831
00:46:36,669 --> 00:46:38,545
Miss Wade is here to see you.

832
00:46:38,713 --> 00:46:41,506
Have her come in, please.
I am finished here.

833
00:46:41,674 --> 00:46:42,841
JANIE:
Yes, sir.

834
00:46:43,009 --> 00:46:44,801
There is no Sydney issue.

835
00:46:48,055 --> 00:46:50,932
LEWIS: Good morning.
- Oh, hi. Hi.

836
00:46:51,100 --> 00:46:53,602
Uh, thanks for seeing me
on such short notice.

837
00:46:53,769 --> 00:46:55,979
No problem.
Did you, uh, get the ham?

838
00:46:56,147 --> 00:46:57,814
Ha, ha, yes, I got the ham.

839
00:46:57,982 --> 00:47:02,110
I wanted to send you some flowers,
but there appear to be kinks in the system.

840
00:47:02,278 --> 00:47:05,947
I'm so glad you stopped by.
I had such a good time last night.

841
00:47:06,657 --> 00:47:09,826
- So did I. Um, it's just that I... Um...
JANIE: They're 45 seconds away.

842
00:47:09,994 --> 00:47:13,413
I have a luncheon speech
at the governors' conference. I'm sorry.

843
00:47:13,581 --> 00:47:16,249
- Are you free for dinner tomorrow evening?
- Dinner?

844
00:47:16,417 --> 00:47:17,459
Casual, in the residence...

845
00:47:17,627 --> 00:47:19,085
...without the United Nations.
- Heh.

846
00:47:19,253 --> 00:47:21,588
My daughter will be there,
so it may seem like it.

847
00:47:21,756 --> 00:47:25,008
- I'd love to meet Lucy...
- She'd love to meet you. Excuse me, Jeff...

848
00:47:25,176 --> 00:47:27,052
Actually, I have some concerns that I...

849
00:47:27,220 --> 00:47:28,512
JEFF: Yes, sir.
- I can't do this.

850
00:47:28,679 --> 00:47:30,889
- Robbins or Stackhouse?
- Either. I have to be in and out.

851
00:47:31,057 --> 00:47:34,226
Stackhouse needs 10 minutes.
I think it's about the assault weapons.

852
00:47:34,393 --> 00:47:37,145
He wants to talk about grazing rights.
Trust me.

853
00:47:37,313 --> 00:47:39,189
I'm sorry. You have concerns?

854
00:47:39,357 --> 00:47:42,108
Yes, uh, not many. A few.

855
00:47:42,276 --> 00:47:43,902
One. I have one concern.

856
00:47:44,070 --> 00:47:46,696
This wouldn't have to do
with the fact that one of us is president?

857
00:47:46,864 --> 00:47:49,199
Ha, ha,
you like to make jokes about this...

858
00:47:49,367 --> 00:47:51,952
I'm not mocking you.
I'm just a guy asking a girl over for a meal.

859
00:47:52,119 --> 00:47:53,411
[HELICOPTER WHIRRING]

860
00:47:53,579 --> 00:47:54,829
What's that?

861
00:47:55,248 --> 00:47:56,831
That's my ride.

862
00:47:57,208 --> 00:47:59,960
Oh, um...

863
00:48:00,127 --> 00:48:04,798
Leo Solomon has some serious concerns
about me exploring a social...

864
00:48:04,966 --> 00:48:06,967
...you know...

865
00:48:07,134 --> 00:48:09,928
...scenario with the president
of the United States.

866
00:48:10,096 --> 00:48:12,556
Put that way,
it doesn't sound good to me either.

867
00:48:12,723 --> 00:48:14,724
Have dinner with Lucy and me.
It's meat loaf night.

868
00:48:14,892 --> 00:48:16,935
- How presidential can that be?
- Uh...

869
00:48:17,103 --> 00:48:18,186
Seven-thirty?

870
00:48:19,397 --> 00:48:20,522
Mm.

871
00:48:20,690 --> 00:48:21,940
Mm-hm.

872
00:48:51,470 --> 00:48:54,055
- Hi. Are you Miss Wade?
- Hi. Uh, Sydney.

873
00:48:54,223 --> 00:48:57,517
- Hi. Lucy Shepherd. Nice to meet you.
- Hi. Nice to meet you.

874
00:48:57,685 --> 00:49:02,939
Um, my dad told me to tell you
that he's on the phone with his dentist...

875
00:49:03,107 --> 00:49:05,900
...and I should behave myself
and entertain you until he gets back.

876
00:49:06,068 --> 00:49:08,528
Ah. Your father's on the phone
with his dentist?

877
00:49:08,696 --> 00:49:11,948
No. He told me to tell you
that he's on the phone with his dentist.

878
00:49:12,116 --> 00:49:14,659
- He wants you to think he's a regular guy.
- Heh, all right.

879
00:49:14,827 --> 00:49:17,954
- Well, who's he on the phone with?
- The Prime Minister of Israel.

880
00:49:18,122 --> 00:49:21,207
- They're probably not discussing his teeth.
- I hope not.

881
00:49:21,375 --> 00:49:22,751
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

882
00:49:22,918 --> 00:49:25,670
They're discussing that abbreviation
I can never remember.

883
00:49:25,838 --> 00:49:28,965
- Mm, C-STAD?
- Yeah.

884
00:49:29,133 --> 00:49:32,677
- Capricorn Surface-to-Air Defense.
- Right.

885
00:49:33,262 --> 00:49:36,264
Okay. Let meat-loaf night begin. Hi.

886
00:49:36,432 --> 00:49:38,475
Hi. How's everything with your teeth?

887
00:49:38,643 --> 00:49:40,310
- My teeth?
- The dentist.

888
00:49:40,478 --> 00:49:41,561
Oh, right. Right, right.

889
00:49:41,729 --> 00:49:44,105
Yeah, I got a cavity
in my upper bicuspid region.

890
00:49:44,273 --> 00:49:47,233
You have a short-range weapons system
outside Tel Aviv.

891
00:49:47,401 --> 00:49:48,818
I think somebody told on me.

892
00:49:48,986 --> 00:49:50,487
[LUCY SHOUTING]

893
00:49:53,240 --> 00:49:56,618
[JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING ON SPEAKERS]

894
00:49:56,786 --> 00:49:59,996
[ALL CHATTERING]

895
00:50:00,164 --> 00:50:02,123
A. J:
Congressman...

896
00:50:02,291 --> 00:50:03,541
You're over-thinking this.

897
00:50:03,709 --> 00:50:07,003
Voters aren't interested
in how to achieve economic growth.

898
00:50:07,171 --> 00:50:10,215
They don't want to hear our plans
to strengthen foreign policy.

899
00:50:10,383 --> 00:50:11,841
So it comes down to character.

900
00:50:12,009 --> 00:50:14,219
Press like him.
The networks, the newspapers...

901
00:50:14,387 --> 00:50:15,887
Reporters like him.

902
00:50:16,055 --> 00:50:19,683
Networks and newspapers
like ratings and circulation.

903
00:50:19,850 --> 00:50:23,395
For all the bitching we do
about liberal bias in the press...

904
00:50:23,562 --> 00:50:25,814
...when it comes to
a good character debate...

905
00:50:25,981 --> 00:50:28,108
The press is an unwitting accomplice.

906
00:50:28,275 --> 00:50:30,151
The character debate didn't work for us.

907
00:50:30,319 --> 00:50:32,112
Because it couldn't.

908
00:50:32,279 --> 00:50:36,491
Our polling told us that attacking him
less than a year after he'd lost his wife...

909
00:50:36,659 --> 00:50:39,828
...was gonna be a turnoff,
was gonna make people feel sorry for him.

910
00:50:39,995 --> 00:50:43,331
We couldn't run the campaign we wanted
because the opponent was a widower.

911
00:50:43,624 --> 00:50:46,251
But he's still a widower, Bob.
Time's passed but...

912
00:50:46,419 --> 00:50:48,169
[ALL CHUCKLE]

913
00:50:48,337 --> 00:50:49,879
You'll have to forgive my friend.

914
00:50:50,047 --> 00:50:52,799
He was on a hunting trip.
He's been cut off from the world.

915
00:50:52,967 --> 00:50:54,384
Why? What's going on?

916
00:51:01,726 --> 00:51:04,269
The president's got a girlfriend.

917
00:51:06,856 --> 00:51:09,441
So you're studying
the Constitutional Convention.

918
00:51:09,608 --> 00:51:11,609
- She's not having any fun, though.
- Dad.

919
00:51:11,861 --> 00:51:13,319
You're not having any fun?

920
00:51:13,487 --> 00:51:16,072
This is a nightmare.
This is a social-studies nightmare.

921
00:51:16,240 --> 00:51:17,615
They're doing a mock congress.

922
00:51:17,783 --> 00:51:21,411
Each kid plays one of the original delegates
and they debate the amendments.

923
00:51:21,579 --> 00:51:22,620
What's not fun?

924
00:51:22,788 --> 00:51:25,373
- Good night, Dad.
- Good night, sweetheart.

925
00:51:27,001 --> 00:51:30,044
- It was nice meeting you, Sydney.
- It was nice to meet you.

926
00:51:30,212 --> 00:51:33,381
- Sleep well, honey. I love you.
- Love you too, Dad.

927
00:51:34,341 --> 00:51:35,717
She's wonderful.

928
00:51:36,093 --> 00:51:37,594
She's her mother.

929
00:51:38,929 --> 00:51:40,221
She's you.

930
00:51:45,603 --> 00:51:47,645
Would you like the 25-cent tour?

931
00:51:48,731 --> 00:51:50,190
Okay.

932
00:51:53,277 --> 00:51:56,029
I thought C-STAD wouldn't be operational
