when we'll have the full B.D.A.

997
00:55:59,690 --> 00:56:02,817
- General Rork says around 0800.
A. J: 0800?

998
00:56:03,402 --> 00:56:05,570
Sir, what do you think
about a national address?

999
00:56:06,488 --> 00:56:09,615
Last thing I want to do
is put the Libyans center stage.

1000
00:56:09,783 --> 00:56:11,409
LEON:
Well, I think it's a great idea.

1001
00:56:11,577 --> 00:56:15,163
You know Rumson is gonna be
talking about your lack of military service.

1002
00:56:15,330 --> 00:56:16,956
It's not about Rumson.

1003
00:56:17,124 --> 00:56:19,834
What I did tonight
was not about political gain.

1004
00:56:20,002 --> 00:56:21,711
Yes, but it can be, sir.

1005
00:56:21,879 --> 00:56:25,131
What you did tonight
was very presidential.

1006
00:56:26,258 --> 00:56:27,842
Leon...

1007
00:56:28,010 --> 00:56:29,761
Somewhere in Libya right now...

1008
00:56:29,928 --> 00:56:33,306
...a janitor's working a night shift
at Libyan Intelligence Headquarters.

1009
00:56:33,474 --> 00:56:35,975
He's going about doing his job...

1010
00:56:36,143 --> 00:56:41,898
...because he has no idea in about an hour
he's going to die in a massive explosion.

1011
00:56:44,777 --> 00:56:46,736
He's just going about his job...

1012
00:56:46,904 --> 00:56:50,031
...because he has no idea
that about an hour ago...

1013
00:56:50,199 --> 00:56:53,034
...I gave an order to have him killed.

1014
00:56:54,453 --> 00:56:58,039
You've just seen me do
the least presidential thing I do.

1015
00:56:59,666 --> 00:57:01,626
[REPORTERS CHATTERING]

1016
00:57:01,794 --> 00:57:02,794
Mary?

1017
00:57:02,961 --> 00:57:05,296
MARY: Is there anything
about the C-STAD system...

1018
00:57:05,464 --> 00:57:09,675
...that could have been mistaken
as offensive rather than defensive?

1019
00:57:09,927 --> 00:57:12,261
No. We did everything
but show them the blueprints.

1020
00:57:12,429 --> 00:57:16,057
The hardware had been sitting in an
airplane hangar for more than a month.

1021
00:57:16,225 --> 00:57:18,935
They didn't hit it
until the American personnel arrived.

1022
00:57:19,103 --> 00:57:22,271
Sir, there's an unconfirmed report
that you were with Sydney Wade...

1023
00:57:22,439 --> 00:57:24,190
...when you learned of the attack.
Comment?

1024
00:57:24,358 --> 00:57:26,234
- Yes, we had just finished dinner.
- Get him off.

1025
00:57:26,401 --> 00:57:27,735
Last question.

1026
00:57:27,903 --> 00:57:30,988
Sir, would you care to comment
on your relationship?

1027
00:57:31,156 --> 00:57:33,991
We don't have a relationship,
we just had dinner. Thank you.

1028
00:57:34,159 --> 00:57:36,119
Did she spend the night
at the White House?

1029
00:57:36,286 --> 00:57:39,789
Folks, a lot of people
were killed last night.

1030
00:57:39,957 --> 00:57:42,917
Let's try to keep our eye on the ball, okay?
Thank you.

1031
00:57:43,085 --> 00:57:45,419
[REPORTERS SPEAKING
INDISTINCTLY]

1032
00:57:45,587 --> 00:57:47,380
That was my fault.
We should have prepped you.

1033
00:57:47,548 --> 00:57:49,549
There's nothing that needs prepping.
A. J?

1034
00:57:49,716 --> 00:57:52,760
Let's meet with the leadership
after we meet the Security Council.

1035
00:57:52,928 --> 00:57:55,304
Newsweek is begging
for 10 minutes today. Any 10.

1036
00:57:55,472 --> 00:57:57,306
Nobody gets 10 minutes today.

1037
00:57:57,850 --> 00:58:00,351
Tell the speaker to wait.
I want to talk to him.

1038
00:58:00,519 --> 00:58:02,854
No, I'll be right down.

1039
00:58:03,021 --> 00:58:05,565
RUMSON [ON TV]: Last night,
the cost of those liberal programs...

1040
00:58:05,732 --> 00:58:10,194
...was raised to include
the blood of 22 American soldiers.

1041
00:58:10,362 --> 00:58:11,863
Mr. Shepherd's read a lot of books...

1042
00:58:12,030 --> 00:58:16,159
...but it doesn't take a Harvard degree to
see this one coming a mile down the road.

1043
00:58:16,326 --> 00:58:18,703
I went to Stanford, you blowhole.

1044
00:58:18,871 --> 00:58:21,706
He has never served one day in uniform.

1045
00:58:23,292 --> 00:58:25,168
BETH:
This box just says "miscellaneous."

1046
00:58:25,335 --> 00:58:26,794
Is it bedroom miscellaneous...

1047
00:58:26,962 --> 00:58:29,130
...or kitchen miscellaneous?

1048
00:58:30,799 --> 00:58:34,677
- Sydney?
- Why did I have to kiss him?

1049
00:58:35,637 --> 00:58:38,306
- You kissed him?
- Yeah.

1050
00:58:39,641 --> 00:58:41,392
- You didn't tell me.
- I kissed him.

1051
00:58:41,560 --> 00:58:43,603
- Where?
- On the mouth.

1052
00:58:43,770 --> 00:58:46,689
- Where in the White House?
- In the Dish Room.

1053
00:58:46,857 --> 00:58:49,984
- The "Dish Room"?
- The China Room.

1054
00:58:50,152 --> 00:58:52,153
And then what happened?

1055
00:58:52,321 --> 00:58:55,031
- He had to go and attack Libya.
- It's always something.

1056
00:58:55,199 --> 00:58:59,368
Yeah, I gotta nip this in the bud.
This has "catastrophe" written all over it.

1057
00:58:59,578 --> 00:59:01,078
In what language?

1058
00:59:01,246 --> 00:59:03,539
Sydney, the man is the leader
of the free world.

1059
00:59:03,707 --> 00:59:07,251
He's brilliant, he's funny, he's handsome,
he's an above-average dancer.

1060
00:59:07,419 --> 00:59:11,505
Isn't it possible
our standards are just a tad high?

1061
00:59:11,673 --> 00:59:14,675
[PHONE RINGING]

1062
00:59:18,013 --> 00:59:19,138
Answer the phone.

1063
00:59:19,306 --> 00:59:20,681
- It's him.
- Answer the phone.

1064
00:59:20,849 --> 00:59:22,183
He's gonna ask me come over.

1065
00:59:22,351 --> 00:59:23,809
- Answer.
- I don't want to go.

1066
00:59:23,977 --> 00:59:24,977
Answer the phone.

1067
00:59:25,145 --> 00:59:27,480
All right.
But I'm gonna end it on the phone.

1068
00:59:29,858 --> 00:59:32,693
Uh, I just came over to tell you
why I can't see you anymore.

1069
00:59:34,446 --> 00:59:36,906
Come on in. Thanks, Coop.

1070
00:59:40,202 --> 00:59:41,953
Uh, look, I know you've had a tough day.

1071
00:59:42,120 --> 00:59:45,581
Not as tough as some. Want a drink?
Let me take your coat.

1072
00:59:45,749 --> 00:59:47,959
Mr. President, this isn't gonna work.

1073
00:59:48,126 --> 00:59:51,837
- Sure it will. Button the top button...
- That's not what I mean.

1074
00:59:52,005 --> 00:59:55,424
- I didn't think it was.
- I've really enjoyed our time together...

1075
00:59:55,592 --> 00:59:58,010
...this has "catastrophe"
written all over it.

1076
00:59:58,178 --> 01:00:02,014
Please, Mr. President, don't pursue me
outside the political arena.

1077
01:00:02,182 --> 01:00:04,934
I have no intentions of pursuing you
inside of it...

1078
01:00:05,102 --> 01:00:08,187
...and that leaves everything out
and that's unacceptable to me.

1079
01:00:08,355 --> 01:00:09,689
If I were on your staff...

1080
01:00:09,856 --> 01:00:13,567
...I'd tell you that the worst thing
you can do, coming into an election year...

1081
01:00:13,735 --> 01:00:17,113
...is open yourself to character attacks.
The quickest way to do that...

1082
01:00:17,281 --> 01:00:19,657
...is to prance around like the playboy
of the Western World.

1083
01:00:19,825 --> 01:00:24,078
Let's clear up a couple of things here.
Number one, I seldom prance.

1084
01:00:24,288 --> 01:00:27,331
Number two, I have no intention
of engaging in a character debate.

1085
01:00:27,499 --> 01:00:31,419
- Number three, you're not on my staff.
- But if you'll follow the immutable...

1086
01:00:31,586 --> 01:00:34,213
Why is that, by the way? Please.

1087
01:00:34,464 --> 01:00:37,425
- Why is what?
- Why aren't you on my staff?

1088
01:00:37,968 --> 01:00:40,344
- You can't afford me.
- How much do you make?

1089
01:00:40,512 --> 01:00:42,013
More than you do, Mr. President.

1090
01:00:42,180 --> 01:00:44,682
The name is Andy.
How much money do you make?

1091
01:00:44,850 --> 01:00:46,767
What does it matter how much I make?

1092
01:00:46,977 --> 01:00:48,769
You raise your voice to the president?

1093
01:00:48,937 --> 01:00:51,731
Ugh, I'm only thinking
about the health of your presidency.

1094
01:00:51,898 --> 01:00:54,942
You know this morning's press conference
won't be the end of this.

1095
01:00:55,110 --> 01:00:57,445
Bob Rumson's gotta be
drooling over this.

1096
01:00:57,612 --> 01:00:59,238
Are you attracted to me?

1097
01:01:00,407 --> 01:01:04,368
- I beg your pardon?
- I asked if you were attracted to me.

1098
01:01:04,536 --> 01:01:05,619
That's not the issue.

1099
01:01:05,787 --> 01:01:09,332
Tell you what. Let's make it the issue.
Let's try something new...

1100
01:01:09,499 --> 01:01:12,668
...because when most couples
first get together, they're inclined...

1101
01:01:12,836 --> 01:01:16,589
...to slam on the brakes because they're
concerned about Bob Rumson's drool.

1102
01:01:16,757 --> 01:01:19,383
- You're not most people.
- You know what your problem is?

1103
01:01:19,551 --> 01:01:20,593
What's my problem?

1104
01:01:21,470 --> 01:01:23,387
Sex and nervousness.

1105
01:01:24,139 --> 01:01:26,599
- Sex and nervousness is my problem?
- Yes.

1106
01:01:26,767 --> 01:01:30,227
Last night when we were looking
at those place settings in the Dish Room...

1107
01:01:30,395 --> 01:01:33,564
...I realized those place settings
were provided by the first ladies.

1108
01:01:33,732 --> 01:01:36,067
I'll bet none of those first ladies...

1109
01:01:36,234 --> 01:01:40,529
...were nervous about having sex
with their president husbands.

1110
01:01:40,697 --> 01:01:42,198
And you know why?

1111
01:01:42,991 --> 01:01:45,743
- No, but I'm sure you'll explain it to me.
- I will.

1112
01:01:46,328 --> 01:01:49,121
Because they weren't presidents
when they first met them.

1113
01:01:49,289 --> 01:01:51,290
That's not the case here.

1114
01:01:52,125 --> 01:01:54,001
- Ah.
- You see what I'm getting at?

1115
01:01:54,169 --> 01:01:55,795
Yes.

1116
01:01:56,338 --> 01:01:57,421
[SIGHS]

1117
01:01:57,589 --> 01:02:01,175
- May I use your bathroom for a moment?
- Right through there. Right behind you.

1118
01:02:01,676 --> 01:02:03,552
I just want to freshen up.

1119
01:02:03,720 --> 01:02:06,597
As you pass through,
you'll see a large closet on the right.

1120
01:02:06,765 --> 01:02:08,766
If you want, hang up your coat.

1121
01:02:08,934 --> 01:02:10,518
Then I'll fix us a drink...

1122
01:02:10,685 --> 01:02:14,230
...we'll sit on the couch,
and I'll explain to you my plan.

1123
01:02:14,398 --> 01:02:17,066
SYDNEY: You got a plan?
Don't make me wait. You're on a roll.

1124
01:02:17,234 --> 01:02:19,527
Okay, you're attracted to me...

1125
01:02:19,903 --> 01:02:22,530
...but the idea of physical intimacy
is uncomfortable...

1126
01:02:22,697 --> 01:02:25,366
...because you only know me
as the president.

1127
01:02:25,534 --> 01:02:27,284
It's not always going to be that way.

1128
01:02:27,452 --> 01:02:30,830
The reason I know that is
there was a moment last night...

1129
01:02:30,997 --> 01:02:34,542
...when you were with me
and not the president.

1130
01:02:34,709 --> 01:02:38,087
And I know what a big step
that was for you.

1131
01:02:38,255 --> 01:02:41,006
So, Sydney, I'm in no rush.

1132
01:02:41,174 --> 01:02:44,051
Here's my plan.
We're gonna slow down...

1133
01:02:44,219 --> 01:02:47,596
...and when you're comfortable,
that's when it's gonna happen.

1134
01:02:58,108 --> 01:03:02,194
Perhaps I didn't properly explain
the fundamentals of the slowdown plan.

1135
01:03:02,612 --> 01:03:04,864
No, you explained it great.

1136
01:03:07,534 --> 01:03:08,993
Are you nervous?

1137
01:03:10,537 --> 01:03:13,164
- No.
- Good.

1138
01:03:13,331 --> 01:03:16,500
My nervousness exists on several levels.

1139
01:03:16,668 --> 01:03:20,087
Number one,
and this is in no particular order:

1140
01:03:20,255 --> 01:03:22,882
I haven't done this in a pretty long time.

1141
01:03:23,216 --> 01:03:25,092
Number two, uh:

1142
01:03:25,260 --> 01:03:30,723
Any expectations that you might have,
given the fact that I'm, you know...

1143
01:03:31,433 --> 01:03:34,143
- The most powerful man in the world.
- Exactly, thank you.

1144
01:03:34,311 --> 01:03:38,063
Remember that it's a political distinction
that comes with the office.

1145
01:03:38,231 --> 01:03:42,902
I mean, if, uh, Eisenhower were here
instead of me he'd be dead by now.

1146
01:03:43,069 --> 01:03:45,196
- And number three...
- Andy.

1147
01:03:46,448 --> 01:03:47,907
RUMSON:
Does New Hampshire want...

1148
01:03:48,074 --> 01:03:51,785
...traditional American values
back in the White House?

1149
01:03:51,953 --> 01:03:55,372
[ALL CHEERING]

1150
01:03:55,540 --> 01:03:58,501
Does New Hampshire
want the pride back?

1151
01:04:01,296 --> 01:04:05,508
My name is Bob Rumson,
and I'm running for president.

1152
01:04:10,847 --> 01:04:12,848
[PHONE RINGING]

1153
01:04:18,813 --> 01:04:20,189
Yeah. Ahem.

1154
01:04:22,901 --> 01:04:24,944
Put him through.

1155
01:04:25,111 --> 01:04:29,865
Lewis, it is 5 a.m.
You've got to get yourself a life, man.

1156
01:04:30,784 --> 01:04:32,034
Yeah.

1157
01:04:32,661 --> 01:04:34,370
All right.

1158
01:04:43,255 --> 01:04:45,923
- Sydney.
- Hi.

1159
01:04:46,258 --> 01:04:47,716
Uh, what are you doing?

1160
01:04:47,884 --> 01:04:52,054
Uh, I wanted to leave the building
before the press corps got here.

1161
01:04:52,681 --> 01:04:55,057
I have those same thoughts
every day of my life.

1162
01:04:55,225 --> 01:04:56,267
[SYDNEY CHUCKLES]

1163
01:04:56,434 --> 01:04:58,143
You know Lewis Rothschild, don't you?

1164
01:04:58,311 --> 01:05:01,605
Sure. Boy, Lewis would go nuts
if he knew I spent the night.

1165
01:05:01,773 --> 01:05:04,024
- Well, he's on his way up.
- What?

1166
01:05:04,192 --> 01:05:05,192
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

1167
01:05:05,360 --> 01:05:06,402
Come on in, Lewis.

1168
01:05:06,570 --> 01:05:08,737
Morning, Mr. President. Hi, Sydney.

1169
01:05:08,905 --> 01:05:11,657
Hi, Lewis. Well, Mr. President...

1170
01:05:12,367 --> 01:05:16,453
Uh, thanks for taking the time
to go over those fossil-fuel numbers.

1171
01:05:16,621 --> 01:05:19,415
I'll just get my coat, be on my way.

1172
01:05:19,583 --> 01:05:22,209
- So, what's the situation?
- Camped out at every exit.

1173
01:05:22,377 --> 01:05:24,378
Who? Who's camped out?

1174
01:05:24,546 --> 01:05:26,714
- The press.
- The press is camped out?

1175
01:05:26,881 --> 01:05:28,007
You should have taken a cab.

1176
01:05:28,174 --> 01:05:29,216
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

1177
01:05:29,384 --> 01:05:31,093
- They know my car?
- Good morning, Sydney.

1178
01:05:31,261 --> 01:05:33,387
- I came as soon as Lewis called.
- Oh, thank God.

1179
01:05:33,555 --> 01:05:35,556
Let's not look like we're panicking.

1180
01:05:35,724 --> 01:05:38,934
See, the important thing is
actually not to be panicking.

1181
01:05:39,102 --> 01:05:40,144
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

1182
01:05:40,312 --> 01:05:42,021
- Morning, Mr. President.
- Morning.

1183
01:05:42,188 --> 01:05:43,522
- Morning, Miss Wade.
SYDNEY: Hello.

1184
01:05:43,690 --> 01:05:45,816
I see everyone's getting
an early start today.

1185
01:05:45,984 --> 01:05:49,320
How do we exit Sydney from the building
and, uh, what do we say to the press?

1186
01:05:49,487 --> 01:05:51,572
- We need a diversion.
- A diversion?

1187
01:05:51,740 --> 01:05:54,241
I'm not suggesting
that we burn the White House.

1188
01:05:54,409 --> 01:05:55,951
Oh, please, let's do.

1189
01:05:56,119 --> 01:05:58,787
I state clearly that I can't be party
to anything illegal.

1190
01:05:58,955 --> 01:06:00,164
Good for you.

1191
01:06:00,332 --> 01:06:03,083
It's always the guy in my job
who ends up doing 18 months...

1192
01:06:03,251 --> 01:06:05,044
...in a minimum security prison.

1193
01:06:05,211 --> 01:06:07,713
- Rest easy. We won't create a diversion.
- No diversion.

1194
01:06:07,881 --> 01:06:10,841
- Somebody will take you home.
A. J: Esther's over in my office.

1195
01:06:11,009 --> 01:06:14,637
- She has the station wagon standing by.
- Good. Now, press statement.

1196
01:06:14,804 --> 01:06:16,055
Sydney...

1197
01:06:16,222 --> 01:06:19,600
When you leave here, you're gonna run
into reporters and photographers.

1198
01:06:19,768 --> 01:06:23,937
They're gonna take your picture every day.
They're gonna ask you questions every day.

1199
01:06:24,105 --> 01:06:27,650
Answer them, don't answer them,
it's entirely up to you.

1200
01:06:28,109 --> 01:06:33,155
The White House has no official position
except to say, "No comment."

1201
01:06:33,323 --> 01:06:35,574
- No comment?
- The White House does not comment...

1202
01:06:35,742 --> 01:06:39,328
...on the president's personal life.
- We can't leave it at that.

1203
01:06:39,496 --> 01:06:41,622
I tell you what, Lewis. We just did.

1204
01:06:41,790 --> 01:06:43,499
- But, sir...
- Thank you, Mr. President.

1205
01:06:43,667 --> 01:06:45,542
Come, friends. Let us away.

1206
01:06:45,710 --> 01:06:48,128
- Thank you, Mr. President.
ROBIN: Thank you, Mr. President.

1207
01:06:48,296 --> 01:06:50,422
Sydney. Esther will be in my office.

1208
01:06:50,590 --> 01:06:52,925
- Take your time.
- Thanks, A.J.

1209
01:06:56,680 --> 01:06:59,223
Heh, I'm sorry about this.

1210
01:07:00,350 --> 01:07:02,059
We'll do it better next time.

1211
01:07:02,227 --> 01:07:05,104
I'm no expert, but I thought we did it
pretty good this time.

1212
01:07:05,689 --> 01:07:07,147
- No, I didn't mean that.
- I know.

1213
01:07:07,315 --> 01:07:08,649
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

1214
01:07:09,150 --> 01:07:11,276
I had a good time.

1215
01:07:11,528 --> 01:07:14,196
Me too. I'll call you.

1216
01:07:14,364 --> 01:07:17,866
- I'll be in Panama, but I'll call you.
- I'd like that.

1217
01:07:18,034 --> 01:07:19,576
Great.

1218
01:07:20,745 --> 01:07:22,705
- Bye.
- Bye.

1219
01:07:32,132 --> 01:07:35,217
All right. Okay. This is good.

1220
01:07:37,178 --> 01:07:38,721
SYDNEY:
What about an incentive program?

1221
01:07:38,888 --> 01:07:41,223
REPORTER 1: Sydney Ellen Wade,
the political strategist...

1222
01:07:41,391 --> 01:07:44,601
...who accompanied President Shepherd
to last week's state dinner...

1223
01:07:44,769 --> 01:07:47,813
...spent the night at the White House
as a guest to the president.

1224
01:07:47,981 --> 01:07:50,441
REPORTER 2: The president returned
from Panama this evening...

1225
01:07:50,608 --> 01:07:53,193
...after a three-day tour
through Central America.

1226
01:07:53,361 --> 01:07:54,820
His first order of business:

1227
01:07:54,988 --> 01:07:58,991
An intimate dinner with Sydney Wade
at a romantic Georgetown bistro.

1228
01:07:59,159 --> 01:08:01,577
REPORTER 3: Conservative and religious
family organizations...

1229
01:08:01,745 --> 01:08:03,829
...are starting to smell blood
in the water...

1230
01:08:03,997 --> 01:08:06,582
...as the polling numbers
of the president are dropping.

1231
01:08:06,750 --> 01:08:08,250
MAN:
Can you tell us how they met?

1232
01:08:08,418 --> 01:08:11,754
REPORTER 4: Showbiz Weekly
was in Hollywood for the star-studded gala.

1233
01:08:11,921 --> 01:08:16,175
Also on tonight's program,
Day 15 of the Sydney Watch.

1234
01:08:16,342 --> 01:08:19,094
Is the world's most eligible bachelor
off the market?

1235
01:08:19,262 --> 01:08:21,513
MAN [ON RADIO]:
All right. Next caller, you're on the air.

1236
01:08:21,681 --> 01:08:23,348
WOMAN [ON RADIO]:
What about Lucy Shepherd?

1237
01:08:23,516 --> 01:08:25,726
Is anyone concerned about this little girl?

1238
01:08:25,894 --> 01:08:28,979
Can we now finally have a serious debate
about family values?

1239
01:08:29,147 --> 01:08:32,065
- Americans can no longer...
REPORTER 5: Political analyst, Ed Earl.

1240
01:08:32,233 --> 01:08:35,110
With the president's job approval
taking an eight-point dip...

1241
01:08:35,278 --> 01:08:38,113
...from his personal best
of 63 percent three weeks ago...

1242
01:08:38,281 --> 01:08:41,116
...should the White House be concerned
that the girlfriend...

1243
01:08:41,284 --> 01:08:43,786
...has left Shepherd vulnerable
to the questions...

1244
01:08:43,953 --> 01:08:45,662
...he was able to avoid three years ago?

1245
01:08:45,830 --> 01:08:47,414
EARL:
They sure ought to be concerned.

1246
01:08:47,582 --> 01:08:50,709
REPORTER 5: How much
will this new wrinkle affect his ability...

1247
01:08:50,877 --> 01:08:52,586
...to put together a win on his crime bill?

1248
01:08:52,754 --> 01:08:54,505
REPORTER 6:
We'll take a commercial break.

1249
01:08:54,672 --> 01:08:58,050
When we come back, we'll meet a junior
high-school classmate of Sydney...

1250
01:08:58,218 --> 01:09:00,135
...who has some intimate details
to share.

1251
01:09:01,262 --> 01:09:03,847
RUMSON:
I agree with you 110 percent, Mrs. Harper.

1252
01:09:04,015 --> 01:09:05,849
That's why I'm up here
in the dead of winter...

1253
01:09:06,017 --> 01:09:07,935
...talking about it with you folks.
Ha-ha-ha.

1254
01:09:08,102 --> 01:09:10,521
That's very generous of you.
And I'll be taking...

1255
01:09:10,688 --> 01:09:12,856
...that money off your hands right now.

1256
01:09:13,733 --> 01:09:15,108
What've you got?

1257
01:09:15,276 --> 01:09:17,778
Call me Santa Claus, senator.
She's got an FBI file.

1258
01:09:17,946 --> 01:09:21,615
- Oh, shit, Stu. My mother's got an FBI file.
- Yeah, but...

1259
01:09:21,783 --> 01:09:23,450
...I got art.

1260
01:09:25,411 --> 01:09:28,247
It's a demonstration outside
the Department of Commerce.

1261
01:09:28,414 --> 01:09:32,125
The picture's old and some of the faces
are obscured by the fire, but...

1262
01:09:32,460 --> 01:09:34,461
...that's a burning flag...

1263
01:09:34,629 --> 01:09:38,048
...and that's Sydney Ellen Wade
right there in front.

1264
01:09:38,424 --> 01:09:43,428
[SING-SONGY]
It's beginning to look a lot like Christmas.

1265
01:09:44,055 --> 01:09:46,515
Harry. No...

1266
01:09:46,683 --> 01:09:49,852
Harry. Think like a father for a second.

1267
01:09:50,019 --> 01:09:53,647
Wouldn't you like your kids to be able
to take a deep breath when they're 30?

1268
01:09:55,483 --> 01:09:57,109
Thank you.

1269
01:09:57,694 --> 01:09:59,945
You're doing the right thing.

1270
01:10:01,072 --> 01:10:02,447
Tote board's heavy.

1271
01:10:02,615 --> 01:10:04,825
How's this?

1272
01:10:05,159 --> 01:10:06,827
[ALL CHEERING]

1273
01:10:06,995 --> 01:10:09,329
Terrell, North Carolina.

1274
01:10:09,581 --> 01:10:11,540
Hey, Syd. I, uh, saw on your schedule...

1275
01:10:11,708 --> 01:10:14,376
...you're meeting with McSorley,
McCluskey and Shane?

1276
01:10:14,878 --> 01:10:18,380
Yeah. The Motown Three said
they'd give me 30 minutes next week.

1277
01:10:18,590 --> 01:10:20,924
Sydney, these are people
who represent people...

1278
01:10:21,092 --> 01:10:22,718
...who make cars for a living.

1279
01:10:22,886 --> 01:10:24,845
- Yeah?
DAVID: Cars, you understand...

1280
01:10:25,013 --> 01:10:26,555
...run on gasoline.

1281
01:10:26,723 --> 01:10:28,891
Hey. I know it's a long shot.

1282
01:10:29,058 --> 01:10:32,352
But if I can get one of them,
it'll be a huge payoff in visibility.

1283
01:10:32,520 --> 01:10:35,981
If we're gonna try, we should do
some prep work. Want to, uh, order in?

1284
01:10:36,149 --> 01:10:38,650
Uh, I can't. I'm having dinner
at the White House.

1285
01:10:38,818 --> 01:10:41,820
- Uh, so let's start early tomorrow. Say, 7:30?
DAVID: Okay.

1286
01:10:41,988 --> 01:10:44,823
I'm, uh, having lunch at the Kremlin,
so we'll have to...

1287
01:10:44,991 --> 01:10:47,242
...start even earlier than that.
- Good night.

1288
01:10:47,410 --> 01:10:49,453
DAVID: In order for me to catch
the plane to Moscow.

1289
01:10:49,621 --> 01:10:51,079
Good night, David.

1290
01:10:51,831 --> 01:10:53,540
[THUNDER CRASHES]

1291
01:10:54,042 --> 01:10:58,670
Douglas, does the NRA have videotapes
of you playing golf with Satan?

1292
01:10:58,838 --> 01:11:00,714
We've softened the assault weapons.

1293
01:11:00,882 --> 01:11:04,551
We're leaving the SKS, the Mini-14
and 250 other types on the street.

1294
01:11:04,719 --> 01:11:08,388
I mean, how much pull
can one lobby have?

1295
01:11:08,848 --> 01:11:11,016
Uh, we'll continue
this conversation tomorrow.

1296
01:11:11,184 --> 01:11:16,063
I'm late for the party fundraiser and,
Douglas, I'll put in a good word for you.

1297
01:11:16,230 --> 01:11:17,481
You're incredibly late.

1298
01:11:17,649 --> 01:11:20,734
Excuse me, I spoke
with the federal mediator in St. Louis.

1299
01:11:20,902 --> 01:11:23,278
Management walked off.
Baggage handlers, pilots...

1300
01:11:23,446 --> 01:11:26,448
...and flight attendants
are getting set to walk out in 48 hours.

1301
01:11:26,616 --> 01:11:30,369
I studied under a Nobel-Prize-winning
economist. You know what he taught me?

1302
01:11:30,536 --> 01:11:34,164
- Never have an airline strike at Christmas?
- I'm going to St. Louis.

1303
01:11:34,332 --> 01:11:37,084
- You can leave straight from the fundraiser.
- Thanks, A.J.

1304
01:11:37,543 --> 01:11:38,710
Good luck, Mr. President.

1305
01:11:39,921 --> 01:11:41,922
Liberty's moving.

1306
01:11:44,592 --> 01:11:47,386
- Mr. President. Can we have a moment?
JANIE: He's incredibly late.

1307
01:11:47,553 --> 01:11:49,680
Hop in, we'll talk in the car.

1308
01:11:51,391 --> 01:11:53,725
SHEPHERD: What is it?
LEWIS: We have a small problem.

1309
01:11:53,893 --> 01:11:56,186
ROBIN: It could've been small.
It's a medium nightmare.

1310
01:11:56,354 --> 01:11:59,523
LEWIS: It's an opportunity.
ROBIN: It could have been if we'd caught it.

1311
01:11:59,691 --> 01:12:01,149
- We caught it.
- At 5:45.

1312
01:12:01,317 --> 01:12:03,819
It doesn't do me any good.
Network news is in make-up.

1313
01:12:03,987 --> 01:12:08,365
- Twelve people work for you...
- Guys, do I have to be here for this?

1314
01:12:08,533 --> 01:12:12,119
Sorry, sir. Uh, it's on the evening news,
it's buried as the third story.

1315
01:12:12,286 --> 01:12:13,787
It's got a bullet.

1316
01:12:13,955 --> 01:12:17,082
Sydney was at a protest rally.
They burned a flag.

1317
01:12:17,250 --> 01:12:19,334
- Today?
LEWIS: About 13 years ago.

1318
01:12:19,502 --> 01:12:22,671
In front of the Department of Commerce.
Anti-apartheid.

1319
01:12:23,673 --> 01:12:25,590
Uh, let me see if I got this.

1320
01:12:25,758 --> 01:12:27,551
The third story on the news...

1321
01:12:27,719 --> 01:12:31,138
...was that someone I didn't know
13 years ago, when I wasn't president...

1322
01:12:31,305 --> 01:12:35,350
...went to a demonstration where no laws
were broken, in protest of something...

1323
01:12:35,518 --> 01:12:39,396
...that so many people were against,
doesn't exist anymore.

1324
01:12:39,564 --> 01:12:42,274
Just out of curiosity,
what was the fourth story?

1325
01:12:42,775 --> 01:12:45,235
Right. See, I think it's important
when we deal with it...

1326
01:12:45,403 --> 01:12:47,154
SHEPHERD:
Don't deal with it.

1327
01:12:47,321 --> 01:12:49,906
- Excuse me?
- Trying to get us to swing at the dirt.

1328
01:12:50,074 --> 01:12:52,159
Nobody wins these fights. It'll go away.

1329
01:12:55,413 --> 01:12:57,831
LEWIS: Sir, I'm not sure
that's the wisest course of action.

1330
01:12:57,999 --> 01:13:00,083
SHEPHERD: Hell.
ROBIN: It's already distracting you.

1331
01:13:01,002 --> 01:13:02,294
SHEPHERD:
No. You reminded me

1332
01:13:02,462 --> 01:13:04,504
I'm supposed to have dinner
with Sydney tonight.

1333
01:13:05,590 --> 01:13:08,467
Oh, it's terrific. Beth, I love it.

1334
01:13:08,634 --> 01:13:12,429
I can't believe I'm loaning you clothes.
I thought you owned everything.

1335
01:13:12,597 --> 01:13:13,722
Well, work clothes.

1336
01:13:13,890 --> 01:13:17,434
I always wear a suit at the White House.
I thought a dress would be nice.

1337
01:13:17,602 --> 01:13:20,479
Go ahead. Try it on.
I brought earrings too.

1338
01:13:20,646 --> 01:13:22,731
[PHONE RINGING]

1339
01:13:22,899 --> 01:13:24,733
- Hello.
SHEPHERD: Hi, what are you doing?

1340
01:13:24,901 --> 01:13:26,985
Uh, just trying on dresses.

1341
01:13:27,153 --> 01:13:29,988
I feel terrible,
but I'll have to cancel our date tonight.

1342
01:13:30,156 --> 01:13:31,865
SYDNEY: Another woman?
- Heh, no.

1343
01:13:32,033 --> 01:13:35,077
I've gotta go to St. Louis
to avert a massive airline strike.

1344
01:13:35,244 --> 01:13:37,537
If I had a nickel for every time
I heard that one.

1345
01:13:37,705 --> 01:13:39,539
Thanks for understanding.
I'll call you later.

1346
01:13:39,707 --> 01:13:41,333
Okay, bye.

1347
01:13:42,460 --> 01:13:44,711
Oh, I hate doing that.
She was trying on dresses.

1348
01:13:44,879 --> 01:13:46,838
LEWIS:
I tell any girl I'm going out with...

1349
01:13:47,006 --> 01:13:50,383
...to assume that all plans are soft
until she receives confirmation...

1350
01:13:50,551 --> 01:13:53,637
...30 minutes beforehand.
- And they find this romantic?

1351
01:13:53,805 --> 01:13:55,597
I say it with a great deal of charm.

1352
01:13:55,765 --> 01:13:58,683
Look! There it is!
Carmen's House of Flowers.

1353
01:13:58,851 --> 01:14:00,227
- Coop, we gotta stop.
LEWIS: What?

1354
01:14:00,394 --> 01:14:01,853
I gotta get her flowers.

1355
01:14:02,021 --> 01:14:03,105
- Here?
- Now?

1356
01:14:03,272 --> 01:14:05,148
That's what men do
when they break a date.

1357
01:14:05,316 --> 01:14:07,526
That's not what men do.
I don't know men who do that.

1358
01:14:07,693 --> 01:14:09,820
I'm gonna hop out at the flower shop.

1359
01:14:09,987 --> 01:14:11,947
- You'll "hop out," sir?
- He's not hopping.

1360
01:14:12,115 --> 01:14:13,490
No hopping, sir.

1361
01:14:13,783 --> 01:14:17,035
- Stay in the car. I'll get the flowers.
SHEPHERD: It's not gonna be personal.

1362
01:14:17,203 --> 01:14:20,455
LEWIS: Let them do a security sweep.
We don't know who's in there.

1363
01:14:20,623 --> 01:14:25,168
The florist is planning an assassination
on the off-chance I might stop by?

1364
01:14:25,336 --> 01:14:26,753
It's possible.

1365
01:14:27,296 --> 01:14:29,256
WOMAN:
No, no.

1366
01:14:29,423 --> 01:14:32,342
You're not hearing me.
Listen to what I'm saying.

1367
01:14:32,552 --> 01:14:35,178
It was at the basketball game.

1368
01:14:35,346 --> 01:14:36,429
Excuse me.

1369
01:14:36,597 --> 01:14:39,141
No, girl, at the game.
Kiki wasn't even there.

1370
01:14:39,308 --> 01:14:41,893
- Excuse me?
- Ha, ha. Ugh, hold on.

1371
01:14:42,270 --> 01:14:44,521
I will be right with you.

1372
01:14:44,689 --> 01:14:47,899
SHEPHERD: I don't know if you're the one
I talked to on the phone...

1373
01:14:48,067 --> 01:14:50,986
Virginia, dogwood, president...

1374
01:14:51,154 --> 01:14:54,197
Does any of this ring a bell?

1375
01:14:54,365 --> 01:14:56,408
Same girl, she remembered me.

1376
01:14:57,410 --> 01:15:00,412
RUMSON: I'm glad to see
that the president has a girlfriend.

1377
01:15:00,580 --> 01:15:02,038
Never mind...

1378
01:15:02,206 --> 01:15:07,294
...that she's the hired gun of an
ultra-liberal political action committee.

1379
01:15:09,046 --> 01:15:10,505
Never mind...

1380
01:15:10,673 --> 01:15:12,924
...that the president takes the 5th...

1381
01:15:13,092 --> 01:15:17,512
...any time a reporter has the temerity
to ask him a question about a woman...

1382
01:15:17,680 --> 01:15:20,849
...in a position
to exert enormous influence...

1383
01:15:21,017 --> 01:15:24,561
...over a huge range of issues.

1384
01:15:25,897 --> 01:15:29,608
Never mind that this woman's idea of how
to unwind at the end of a tough day...

1385
01:15:29,775 --> 01:15:32,319
...is to get together with her ACLU pals...

1386
01:15:32,570 --> 01:15:34,863
...and to set American flags on fire.

1387
01:15:37,533 --> 01:15:40,493
No reaction from the White House.

1388
01:15:41,287 --> 01:15:43,705
SHEPHERD: It doesn't need to be dignified
with a response.

1389
01:15:43,873 --> 01:15:46,333
There's no upside. I'm leaving it alone.

1390
01:15:46,584 --> 01:15:48,251
SYDNEY:
What do Lewis and Robin think?

1391
01:15:48,419 --> 01:15:50,337
Brutus and Cassius, heh?

1392
01:15:50,504 --> 01:15:53,256
They want me to get into
a character debate and mix it up.

1393
01:15:53,424 --> 01:15:55,717
Lewis and Robin are very smart.

1394
01:15:55,885 --> 01:15:58,845
- Sydney says you guys are really stupid.
SYDNEY: I didn't say that.

1395
01:15:59,013 --> 01:16:02,307
- She's questioning your loyalty.
- I question it all the time.

1396
01:16:02,475 --> 01:16:05,227
Wait a minute.
Here comes my favorite part.

1397
01:16:05,394 --> 01:16:09,689
My name is Bob Rumson
and I'm running for president.

1398
01:16:09,857 --> 01:16:14,319
Glad he cleared that up because the crowd
was about to buy some Amway products.

1399
01:16:14,487 --> 01:16:16,363
His numbers are climbing.

1400
01:16:16,530 --> 01:16:18,657
Sydney, his numbers
have nowhere to go but up.

1401
01:16:18,824 --> 01:16:20,617
SYDNEY:
What about yours?

1402
01:16:20,785 --> 01:16:24,246
Ugh, we'll be back up in the 60s
once I get the votes for the crime bill.

1403
01:16:24,413 --> 01:16:25,830
So, what are you doing this weekend?

1404
01:16:25,998 --> 01:16:29,167
Uh, I've got work
I was going to bring home. Why?

1405
01:16:29,335 --> 01:16:31,127
Well, negotiations are going pretty well.

1406
01:16:31,295 --> 01:16:34,172
Looks like the nation's
going to keep on flying and, uh...

1407
01:16:34,340 --> 01:16:36,841
...Lucy's spending Saturday night
at a friend's house.

1408
01:16:37,009 --> 01:16:38,551
What do you have in mind?

1409
01:16:42,056 --> 01:16:43,640
You ever been to Camp David?

1410
01:16:43,808 --> 01:16:45,058
[CHUCKLES]

1411
01:16:45,226 --> 01:16:47,894
Camp David. Sure.
I used to go there all the time...

1412
01:16:48,062 --> 01:16:50,522
...but then they changed chefs and I...

1413
01:16:50,690 --> 01:16:53,733
It's sass, right? You're sassing me.

1414
01:16:53,901 --> 01:16:55,443
Ha, ha, yes.

1415
01:16:55,611 --> 01:16:58,363
I'm gonna have somebody pick you up
on Saturday morning.

1416
01:16:58,531 --> 01:17:00,740
Okay. Bye.

1417
01:17:00,908 --> 01:17:02,367
Bye.

1418
01:17:15,756 --> 01:17:19,092
SYDNEY: Mm, good God.
SHEPHERD: What?

1419
01:17:19,260 --> 01:17:22,762
SYDNEY: I'm looking at your college
transcripts. This isn't human.

1420
01:17:22,930 --> 01:17:26,891
Nobody gets this many A's.
You were like a Stepford student. Ha, ha.

1421
01:17:27,059 --> 01:17:29,060
Still reading that ridiculous biography?

1422
01:17:29,228 --> 01:17:31,771
No. I finished
Shepherd: Road to the White House.

1423
01:17:31,939 --> 01:17:34,399
Now I'm on to
Shepherd: The Early Years.

1424
01:17:34,567 --> 01:17:37,402
SHEPHERD: Seven trillion dollar
communication system at my disposal...

1425
01:17:37,570 --> 01:17:42,824
...and I can't find out if the Packers won.
- Oh, Andy. C-minus in Women's Studies.

1426
01:17:42,992 --> 01:17:44,034
That course wasn't about...

1427
01:17:44,201 --> 01:17:46,369
...what I thought it was going to be about.
- Ha-ha-ha.

1428
01:17:46,537 --> 01:17:48,872
MAN [ON TV]: President Shepherd
was in Maryland this week...

1429
01:17:49,040 --> 01:17:51,750
...for his routine physical exam.

1430
01:17:51,917 --> 01:17:56,463
Doctors at Bethesda Naval Hospital
pronounced him in excellent health.

1431
01:17:56,630 --> 01:18:00,175
Who cares? Just give us the scores.

1432
01:18:00,718 --> 01:18:03,386
REPORTER [ON TV]: While the president
spent the day at Camp David...

1433
01:18:03,554 --> 01:18:04,929
...GOP presidential hopeful...

1434
01:18:05,097 --> 01:18:09,267
...Robert Rumson, continued his attacks
on President Shepherd's character.

1435
01:18:09,435 --> 01:18:13,521
During the Saturday news program,
Capitol Review with Kenneth Michaels...

1436
01:18:13,689 --> 01:18:15,565
...Senator Rumson suggested that...

1437
01:18:15,733 --> 01:18:18,151
...GDC political director,
Sydney Ellen Wade...

1438
01:18:18,319 --> 01:18:21,112
...whose close personal relationship
with the president...

1439
01:18:21,280 --> 01:18:24,157
...has caused the White House headaches
for two months...

1440
01:18:24,325 --> 01:18:29,454
...may have traded sexual favors for key
votes in the Virginia State Legislature...

1441
01:18:29,622 --> 01:18:32,665
...while lobbying for
the Virginia Teachers Association.

1442
01:18:33,501 --> 01:18:36,753
- That's a heck of an accusation to make...
- I'm not saying...

1443
01:18:36,921 --> 01:18:39,756
Let me be very clear.
I'm not making an accusation.

1444
01:18:39,924 --> 01:18:43,051
I am saying, when you hear one thing,
you dismiss it.

1445
01:18:43,219 --> 01:18:44,552
You hear two, you dismiss it.

1446
01:18:44,720 --> 01:18:49,599
But when several, several well-respected
members and former members...

1447
01:18:49,767 --> 01:18:52,727
...of the Virginia State Legislature...
MAN: Can you give us names?

1448
01:18:52,895 --> 01:18:56,439
- He's making this up as he goes along.
- I'm so sorry, Sydney.

1449
01:18:56,607 --> 01:18:59,109
I don't know what we call her.
The First Mistress?

1450
01:18:59,276 --> 01:19:02,070
Oh, man. My father heard that.

1451
01:19:02,238 --> 01:19:04,447
He's just gonna have to turn a deaf ear.

1452
01:19:04,615 --> 01:19:07,742
My father doesn't have a deaf ear.
He hears fine out of both.

1453
01:19:07,910 --> 01:19:10,787
So do I and so does my sister
and so does my friends.

1454
01:19:10,955 --> 01:19:12,205
You're the only one who...

1455
01:19:12,373 --> 01:19:15,750
I can't challenge a school bully to a fight
because he picks on my girlfriend.

1456
01:19:15,918 --> 01:19:20,713
I'm not asking you to. I can take care
of myself. It's not about me.

1457
01:19:20,881 --> 01:19:22,966
How can you keep quiet?

1458
01:19:23,134 --> 01:19:26,177
How do you have patience for people
who claim to love America...

1459
01:19:26,345 --> 01:19:28,596
...but clearly can't stand Americans?

1460
01:19:29,765 --> 01:19:34,519
I have one election left. I don't have
the luxury of losing my patience.

1461
01:19:37,314 --> 01:19:42,068
I, um... I want to say something to you
but I'm going to fumble it a little bit.

1462
01:19:42,319 --> 01:19:46,156
So, please, just wait till I'm done
before you respond.

1463
01:19:46,323 --> 01:19:47,574
[SIGHS]

1464
01:19:47,741 --> 01:19:51,161
I'm in love with you. I'm certain of it.

1465
01:19:51,328 --> 01:19:54,539
And I want to be with you
more than anything...

1466
01:19:54,707 --> 01:19:59,335
...but maybe things would be better for you
if I just disappeared for a while.

1467
01:20:01,005 --> 01:20:04,132
Things will be better
when I pass the crime bill.

1468
01:20:04,300 --> 01:20:06,468
And if you disappeared...

1469
01:20:06,635 --> 01:20:08,344
...I'd find you.

1470
01:20:09,138 --> 01:20:11,181
[BOTH CHUCKLE]

1471
01:20:16,979 --> 01:20:18,563
SHEPHERD: Hi, Gil.
GIL: Mr. President...

1472
01:20:18,731 --> 01:20:22,817
Um, Mr. President, militant women are out
to destroy college football in this country.

1473
01:20:22,985 --> 01:20:24,611
SHEPHERD: Is that a fact?
GIL: Yes, sir.

1474
01:20:24,778 --> 01:20:27,447
Have you been following
the situation down in Atlanta?

1475
01:20:27,615 --> 01:20:33,244
No. Uh, these women want parity
for girls' softball, volleyball, field hockey...

1476
01:20:33,412 --> 01:20:37,207
If I'm not mistaken, the courts
ruled on Title IX about 20 years ago.

1477
01:20:37,374 --> 01:20:41,085
Yes, sir, but what I'm saying now is
these women want that law enforced.

1478
01:20:41,253 --> 01:20:43,254
- It's a world gone mad.
- It is, sir.

1479
01:20:43,422 --> 01:20:45,173
- Merry Christmas.
- Merry Christmas.

1480
01:20:45,341 --> 01:20:46,466
Come meet some people.

1481
01:20:47,468 --> 01:20:49,427
LEON:
You see, the country has mood swings.

1482
01:20:49,595 --> 01:20:50,803
LEWIS: Mood swings?
LEON: Yeah.

1483
01:20:50,971 --> 01:20:54,557
Nineteen postgraduate degrees
in math and your best explanation...

1484
01:20:54,725 --> 01:20:58,144
...for going from a 63 to 46 percent
approval rating in five weeks...

1485
01:20:58,312 --> 01:20:59,437
...is mood swings?

1486
01:20:59,605 --> 01:21:03,358
Well, I could explain it better,
but I'd need charts, graphs and an easel.

1487
01:21:03,526 --> 01:21:05,777
Fellas, we haven't slept in three years.

1488
01:21:05,945 --> 01:21:09,489
Can't we forget about work for one night
and enjoy each other as friends?

1489
01:21:09,657 --> 01:21:11,783
- It's Christmas.
- It's Christmas?

1490
01:21:11,951 --> 01:21:13,952
Yeah. You didn't get the memo?

1491
01:21:18,249 --> 01:21:21,417
ESTHER: Sydney. Merry Christmas.
- Hi, Esther, hi.

1492
01:21:21,585 --> 01:21:22,794
A. J:
Hello, Sydney.

1493
01:21:22,962 --> 01:21:24,128
Merry Christmas, A.J.

1494
01:21:24,296 --> 01:21:26,631
And a merry Christmas to you.
Where have you been?

1495
01:21:26,799 --> 01:21:28,258
I got stuck on Dupont Circle.

1496
01:21:28,425 --> 01:21:29,926
[ALL CHUCKLE]

1497
01:21:30,094 --> 01:21:33,638
I can never remember which lane
I'm supposed to take.

1498
01:21:33,806 --> 01:21:36,015
Then I got cut off by
this idiot cab driver...

1499
01:21:36,183 --> 01:21:38,101
...who starts screaming at me
that it's my fault.

1500
01:21:38,269 --> 01:21:39,561
Come on, it's Christmas.

1501
01:21:39,728 --> 01:21:42,313
Hi, Syd. Did you get stuck
on Dupont Circle again?

1502
01:21:42,481 --> 01:21:43,815
[ALL LAUGH]

1503
01:21:43,983 --> 01:21:45,608
It's not funny. I hate that place.

1504
01:21:45,818 --> 01:21:48,319
Can't you declare it
a federal disaster area?

1505
01:21:48,487 --> 01:21:51,281
- I'll look into it.
- What were you doing up on the hill?

1506
01:21:51,448 --> 01:21:53,783
Oh, I had a terrible meeting today.

1507
01:21:53,951 --> 01:21:56,369
I totally lost my cool
with McSorley, McCluskey and Shane.

1508
01:21:56,537 --> 01:21:59,289
Heh, you went up to see
the Motown Three?

1509
01:21:59,456 --> 01:22:00,540
I pitched them the bill.

1510
01:22:00,708 --> 01:22:03,293
- On its merits?
- The woman has no fear.

1511
01:22:03,460 --> 01:22:06,796
She'd lobby the Carolinas
for the American Lung Association.

1512
01:22:06,964 --> 01:22:09,090
- It was a disaster.
A. J: You're in good company.

1513
01:22:09,258 --> 01:22:12,594
I sat with them. They said there was
nothing on the domestic agenda...

1514
01:22:12,761 --> 01:22:15,722
...they were more committed to defeating
than the crime bill.

1515
01:22:15,889 --> 01:22:17,724
Well, congratulations, fellas.

1516
01:22:17,891 --> 01:22:20,935
Because McSorley told me
the only thing on the domestic agenda...

1517
01:22:21,103 --> 01:22:25,315
...that they were more committed to
defeating was the fossil-fuel package.

1518
01:22:25,733 --> 01:22:27,942
- You're kidding?
SYDNEY: No, I'm not kidding.

1519
01:22:28,110 --> 01:22:30,320
It's funny, that he used the same words.

1520
01:22:30,487 --> 01:22:32,697
Yeah, Pep Boys don't know
too many words.

1521
01:22:32,865 --> 01:22:36,534
I'm gonna get a drink and shake this off.
Then I'll have some Christmas spirit.

1522
01:22:36,702 --> 01:22:38,202
Okay.

1523
01:22:39,163 --> 01:22:40,622
Are you okay?

1524
01:22:40,789 --> 01:22:42,498
I'm fine, yeah. Heh, I'm fine.

1525
01:22:42,666 --> 01:22:45,460
- Come on, I'll lead the way.
- Thank you.

1526
01:22:45,628 --> 01:22:49,422
BOB: Merry Christmas, Mr. President.
- Happy holidays, Bob.

1527
01:22:49,632 --> 01:22:52,050
Did what I think just happened
just happen?

1528
01:22:52,217 --> 01:22:55,803
Did the GDC's political director tell
the president and the chief of staff...

1529
01:22:55,971 --> 01:22:58,723
...that three votes on the crime bill
can be bought...

1530
01:22:58,891 --> 01:23:00,892
...by sticking the fossil-fuel package
in a drawer?

1531
01:23:01,060 --> 01:23:03,811
No, GDC's political director
didn't tell us anything.

1532
01:23:03,979 --> 01:23:07,815
Sydney Wade told her boyfriend and
his best friend that she had a lousy day.

1533
01:23:07,983 --> 01:23:10,151
It doesn't change the facts,
Mr. President.

1534
01:23:10,319 --> 01:23:14,989
If Sydney gets her 24 votes and we're three
votes shy, there's maneuvering to be done.

1535
01:23:15,157 --> 01:23:16,783
- I made a promise.
- You made a deal.

1536
01:23:16,950 --> 01:23:18,951
- I made it with Sydney.
- With the GDC.

1537
01:23:19,119 --> 01:23:21,496
It's all academic.
We won't need those three votes.

1538
01:23:21,664 --> 01:23:27,627
Sir, if your approval rating continues
to drop, things are going to get tight.

1539
01:23:30,547 --> 01:23:33,424
I've been hearing rumors that your boss
is wavering on the crime bill.

1540
01:23:33,592 --> 01:23:36,386
Heh, I wouldn't listen to rumors.
You know this town.

1541
01:23:36,553 --> 01:23:38,221
That's what I wanted to hear.

1542
01:23:38,430 --> 01:23:41,849
I'll tell you, my boss is starting to waver
on the crime bill.

1543
01:23:42,017 --> 01:23:46,354
Sydney, everybody cares about
the environment during a phone survey.

1544
01:23:46,522 --> 01:23:51,275
On election day, nobody gives a damn.
That's, uh... That's why you have a job.

1545
01:23:51,443 --> 01:23:53,152
Congressman, on election day...

1546
01:23:53,320 --> 01:23:56,364
...people give a damn about what I tell them
to give a damn about.

1547
01:23:56,532 --> 01:23:57,657
That's why I have a job.

1548
01:23:58,575 --> 01:24:00,201
She got Pennybaker.

1549
01:24:00,369 --> 01:24:02,662
[CHEERING]

1550
01:24:02,830 --> 01:24:05,206
LEWIS: It was our understanding
we had your support.

1551
01:24:05,374 --> 01:24:08,167
Look, I like you, boy. Always have.

1552
01:24:08,335 --> 01:24:11,254
But for God's sake,
does the woman have to spend the night?

1553
01:24:11,505 --> 01:24:14,424
We've got the full backing
of the White House, Katherine.

1554
01:24:14,591 --> 01:24:16,551
Yes, at 20 percent.

1555
01:24:16,719 --> 01:24:19,679
Three more votes.
The president sends it to the Hill.

1556
01:24:20,681 --> 01:24:22,390
Katey, Katey...

1557
01:24:22,558 --> 01:24:26,602
Ten years from now, any car with an internal
combustion engine will be a collectible.

1558
01:24:26,770 --> 01:24:29,230
Come onboard.
We'll make your Volvo a classic.

1559
01:24:29,398 --> 01:24:31,482
Congressman,
the assault weapons are gone.

1560
01:24:31,650 --> 01:24:33,067
The bill is priced to move.

1561
01:24:33,235 --> 01:24:36,070
The bill isn't the issue.

1562
01:24:36,238 --> 01:24:38,990
I'm facing a serious challenge
in November.

1563
01:24:39,158 --> 01:24:41,701
The president's coattails aren't
what they used to be.

1564
01:24:41,869 --> 01:24:45,371
The president's coattails will have room
for you. You just leave that to us.

1565
01:24:45,539 --> 01:24:48,416
We left that to you
and now the president's in a free fall.

1566
01:24:48,584 --> 01:24:50,960
LEON: I wouldn't say he's in a free fall...
- Fellas.

1567
01:24:51,628 --> 01:24:53,504
I just can't give you my vote.

1568
01:24:53,672 --> 01:24:57,717
A.J., the well is drying up. He's gotta make
a move or we'll die fast and quiet.

1569
01:24:57,885 --> 01:25:00,178
So, what if I do
a detailed, public-opinion poll?

1570
01:25:00,345 --> 01:25:02,638
- And we put Sydney in the new model.
- Right.

1571
01:25:04,016 --> 01:25:06,768
A.J., it's meaningless
unless we ask them about Sydney.

1572
01:25:09,396 --> 01:25:11,439
All right, fine. Let's do it.

1573
01:25:13,108 --> 01:25:16,903
[PEOPLE CHATTERING]

1574
01:25:17,988 --> 01:25:19,947
[OPERA MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO]

1575
01:25:30,584 --> 01:25:33,169
Mm. Mm. Oh!

1576
01:25:33,337 --> 01:25:35,713
It's delicious. Thank you.

1577
01:25:36,298 --> 01:25:39,467
- Is there any more?
- Tons. I didn't think you liked it.

1578
01:25:39,635 --> 01:25:41,719
You kidding? Of course, I did.

1579
01:25:41,887 --> 01:25:45,807
It's not for me. The agent who checked
the food thought it was delicious too.

1580
01:25:45,974 --> 01:25:47,350
I told him I'd bring him some.

1581
01:25:47,518 --> 01:25:50,269
- So you didn't like it.
- No, I loved it.

1582
01:25:50,437 --> 01:25:51,979
- You're lying.
- No, I'm not.

1583
01:25:52,147 --> 01:25:55,691
I can tell when you're holding something
back. You do a thing with your face.

1584
01:25:55,859 --> 01:25:58,402
When have you ever seen me
do a thing with my face?

1585
01:25:58,570 --> 01:26:00,196
Two days before I met you.

1586
01:26:00,364 --> 01:26:04,617
You gave a speech for the Daughters
of the American Revolution. I was there.

1587
01:26:04,785 --> 01:26:06,744
- You were?
- You remember the speech?

1588
01:26:06,912 --> 01:26:07,954
Vaguely.

1589
01:26:08,121 --> 01:26:11,457
"Americans can no longer afford to pretend
they live in a great society."

1590
01:26:11,625 --> 01:26:12,667
Ah, yes.

1591
01:26:12,835 --> 01:26:16,337
- There was supposed to be something after.
- How did you know that?

1592
01:26:16,797 --> 01:26:19,006
I've told you, the face.

1593
01:26:23,220 --> 01:26:24,387
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

1594
01:26:27,933 --> 01:26:29,892
Ooh, wow! Mm.

1595
01:26:30,060 --> 01:26:31,519
What's the occasion?

1596
01:26:31,687 --> 01:26:34,814
You're looking at a lady
who's two votes shy of the promised land.

1597
01:26:34,982 --> 01:26:37,066
- Two votes?
- I got Pennybaker.

1598
01:26:37,317 --> 01:26:41,153
- That got me Cass and Zimmer.
- That's great. That's great work, Sydney.

1599
01:26:41,321 --> 01:26:42,530
Well, I'm not there, yet.

1600
01:26:42,698 --> 01:26:45,908
No matter what happens, you have
every reason to be proud of yourself.

1601
01:26:46,118 --> 01:26:48,578
No, I'll be proud
when I see you sign the bill.

1602
01:26:49,246 --> 01:26:50,913
Well, yeah.

1603
01:26:51,832 --> 01:26:53,082
Andy...

1604
01:26:53,584 --> 01:26:55,751
You're doing that thing with your face.

1605
01:26:59,923 --> 01:27:02,008
How are the numbers?

1606
01:27:02,175 --> 01:27:03,634
- Bad.
ROBIN: How bad?

1607
01:27:03,802 --> 01:27:05,720
Forty-one. Character, across the board.

1608
01:27:05,888 --> 01:27:07,889
Oh, come on, George, don't tell me that!

1609
01:27:08,056 --> 01:27:10,433
- Who is Lewis on with?
LEON: Jarrett.

1610
01:27:10,767 --> 01:27:12,268
Trying to keep his fingers in the dam.

1611
01:27:12,436 --> 01:27:15,396
You're supposed to be
a United States' Congressman.

1612
01:27:16,189 --> 01:27:20,484
But we're not gonna stay at 41.
The numbers are gonna go back up.

1613
01:27:20,652 --> 01:27:22,486
But they're gonna go back up.

1614
01:27:22,946 --> 01:27:25,364
All right, George... Congressman.

1615
01:27:25,741 --> 01:27:29,368
Congressman Jarrett...
Look, George, listen to me.

1616
01:27:29,536 --> 01:27:31,829
It's crunch time. It's personal.

1617
01:27:31,997 --> 01:27:34,957
This is one of those moments.
It's just you and the president.

1618
01:27:35,125 --> 01:27:37,251
Now, what's it going to be?

1619
01:27:40,130 --> 01:27:41,380
Yeah.

1620
01:27:43,091 --> 01:27:46,052
Yeah. Yeah, all right.
Can I tell you something?

1621
01:27:46,219 --> 01:27:49,096
We're gonna win this thing.
We'll get the votes and we'll win.

1622
01:27:49,264 --> 01:27:51,182
You know what I'm gonna do
that very night?

1623
01:27:51,350 --> 01:27:53,517
I'll go to Sam and Harry's
and order a big steak...

1624
01:27:53,685 --> 01:27:56,145
...and make a list of everybody
who tried to fuck us this week!

1625
01:27:56,313 --> 01:27:58,230
- Lewis!
- Yeah, well, just vote your conscience...

1626
01:27:58,398 --> 01:28:00,650
...you chicken-shit lame-ass!

1627
01:28:03,153 --> 01:28:04,445
We lost Jarrett.

1628
01:28:04,613 --> 01:28:09,367
I hope so. If that was an undecided,
then we need to work on our people skills.

1629
01:28:09,576 --> 01:28:10,910
Yeah, hi, Karen, it's Lewis.

1630
01:28:11,078 --> 01:28:13,955
I need you to find Congressman Quincy
for me right away.

1631
01:28:17,751 --> 01:28:19,502
We lost Quincy too.

1632
01:28:22,673 --> 01:28:24,256
Did he give a reason?

1633
01:28:24,591 --> 01:28:27,385
Yeah, he thinks your numbers
aren't likely to rebound.

1634
01:28:29,513 --> 01:28:32,014
LEON:
We're three votes down again, sir.

1635
01:28:33,850 --> 01:28:37,561
Mr. President, as of this morning,
Sydney only needed one more vote.

1636
01:28:37,729 --> 01:28:39,772
The Motown Three
have gotta be scared blind.

1637
01:28:39,940 --> 01:28:42,441
I don't think there will be
a better opportunity.

1638
01:28:42,609 --> 01:28:46,320
The press expects an announcement
on the crime bill by the State of the Union.

1639
01:28:46,488 --> 01:28:49,407
If you agree to stick 455 in the drawer
until after the elections...

1640
01:28:49,574 --> 01:28:53,160
...they'll give you the three votes.
ROBIN: And we declare victory, sir.

1641
01:28:54,871 --> 01:28:57,331
We said, "as a last resort."

1642
01:28:57,499 --> 01:29:00,292
We're there, sir.
State of the Union is 48 hours away.

1643
01:29:00,460 --> 01:29:03,004
- There must be three votes someplace.
LEON: There isn't.

1644
01:29:03,171 --> 01:29:05,464
- Bullshit! There's gotta be.
LEON: There isn't.

1645
01:29:05,632 --> 01:29:07,008
- Storch.
- Beg your pardon?

1646
01:29:07,175 --> 01:29:09,176
- What about Storch?
- No, Storch is a "no."

1647
01:29:09,344 --> 01:29:10,886
Mr. President...

1648
01:29:11,388 --> 01:29:12,888
- Wagner?
LEON: No.

1649
01:29:13,056 --> 01:29:14,932
- Sobel? Clark?
- No. No.

1650
01:29:15,100 --> 01:29:16,851
Not that Clark. The one from Indiana.

1651
01:29:17,019 --> 01:29:18,602
That one too, sir.

1652
01:29:18,979 --> 01:29:20,896
Mr. President.
I think we have to do this.

1653
01:29:21,064 --> 01:29:23,983
A.J., she is one vote away.

1654
01:29:24,151 --> 01:29:28,029
It's important legislation that
for the first time has a legitimate chance.

1655
01:29:28,196 --> 01:29:31,240
- She deserves every opportunity.
LEWIS: "She"?

1656
01:29:32,200 --> 01:29:33,826
You meant "it," didn't you, sir?

1657
01:29:34,369 --> 01:29:36,871
"The legislation" deserves
every opportunity.

1658
01:29:37,039 --> 01:29:39,874
- Lewis, shut up.
- You have something to say to me, Lewis?

1659
01:29:40,500 --> 01:29:42,418
Respectfully, sir...

1660
01:29:42,586 --> 01:29:45,171
We should examine the new poll
for something more...

1661
01:29:45,338 --> 01:29:49,133
- They don't like me going out with Sydney?
- It's not that simple.

1662
01:29:49,301 --> 01:29:52,470
I think this poll brings a murky problem
into specific relief.

1663
01:29:52,637 --> 01:29:55,514
Whose problem are we talking about,
Lewis? Yours?

1664
01:29:55,682 --> 01:29:57,516
You worried about losing your job?

1665
01:29:57,684 --> 01:30:00,311
Because this poll
isn't talking about my presidency.

1666
01:30:00,479 --> 01:30:02,980
This poll is talking about my life!

1667
01:30:03,774 --> 01:30:07,943
- Two hundred sixty-four million people...
- They don't give a damn about your life.

1668
01:30:08,111 --> 01:30:10,780
- They give a damn about their own!
- All right, that's enough.

1669
01:30:10,947 --> 01:30:11,989
[LEWIS SIGHS]

1670
01:30:12,157 --> 01:30:13,449
Mr. President...

1671
01:30:13,617 --> 01:30:15,493
You raised a daughter...

1672
01:30:15,952 --> 01:30:18,329
...almost entirely on your own...

1673
01:30:18,497 --> 01:30:19,997
...and she's terrific.

1674
01:30:20,665 --> 01:30:24,752
So, what does it say to you, that in the past
seven weeks, 59 percent of this country...

1675
01:30:24,920 --> 01:30:27,254
...has begun to question
your family values?

1676
01:30:27,422 --> 01:30:31,008
- The president doesn't answer to you.
- Oh, yes, he does. I'm a citizen.

1677
01:30:31,176 --> 01:30:32,760
This is my president.

1678
01:30:32,928 --> 01:30:37,431
In this country, it's not only permissible to
question our leaders, it's our responsibility.

1679
01:30:37,933 --> 01:30:40,851
But you already know that,
don't you, Mr. President?

1680
01:30:41,019 --> 01:30:44,980
Because you have a deeper love of this
country than any man I've ever known.

1681
01:30:45,315 --> 01:30:48,609
And I want to know what it says to you
that in the past seven weeks...

1682
01:30:48,777 --> 01:30:51,862
...59 percent of Americans
have begun to question your patriotism?

1683
01:30:52,030 --> 01:30:54,782
- If people want to listen...
LEWIS: They don't have a choice!

1684
01:30:54,950 --> 01:30:57,910
Bob Rumson is the only one
doing the talking.

1685
01:30:58,120 --> 01:31:01,497
People want leadership.
In the absence of genuine leadership...

1686
01:31:01,665 --> 01:31:04,416
...they'll listen to anyone
who steps up to the microphone.

1687
01:31:04,876 --> 01:31:07,128
They want leadership.

1688
01:31:07,295 --> 01:31:10,214
They're so thirsty for it,
they'll crawl through the desert...

1689
01:31:10,382 --> 01:31:13,259
...and if there's no water,
they'll drink the sand.

1690
01:31:15,428 --> 01:31:18,597
Lewis, we have had presidents
who were beloved...

1691
01:31:18,765 --> 01:31:23,227
...who couldn't find a coherent sentence
with two hands and a flashlight.

1692
01:31:24,479 --> 01:31:27,648
People don't drink the sand
because they're thirsty.

1693
01:31:27,816 --> 01:31:31,861
They drink the sand
because they don't know the difference.

1694
01:31:40,036 --> 01:31:41,537
Mr. President...

1695
01:31:41,788 --> 01:31:43,873
What do you want to do about 455?

1696
01:31:47,794 --> 01:31:49,253
Make the deal.

1697
01:31:49,421 --> 01:31:50,963
A. J:
Yes, sir.

1698
01:31:51,298 --> 01:31:53,215
[PEOPLE LAUGHING]

1699
01:31:53,884 --> 01:31:57,595
I just want to go on record and apologize
for my attitude towards you...

1700
01:31:57,762 --> 01:32:00,723
...since your arrival.
- I didn't notice. Was there an attitude?

1701
01:32:00,891 --> 01:32:05,019
Well, I think that, uh...
That I have a lot of pent-up hostility...

1702
01:32:05,187 --> 01:32:07,605
...and I'm wondering
who I should blame that on.

1703
01:32:07,772 --> 01:32:09,565
I'm not qualified to...

1704
01:32:09,733 --> 01:32:12,610
I've been blaming it on my mother
and my ex-husband...

1705
01:32:12,777 --> 01:32:17,156
...and, well, that doesn't seem to work.
- Syd. Leo needs to see you.

1706
01:32:17,324 --> 01:32:21,076
- Well, tell him to get in here. It's a party.
- He needs to see you in his office.

1707
01:32:21,578 --> 01:32:22,745
It can't wait?

1708
01:32:22,913 --> 01:32:26,665
He just got off the phone with Maclnerney.
There's been a development.

1709
01:32:31,922 --> 01:32:33,297
Good evening.

1710
01:32:33,465 --> 01:32:37,176
[LUCY PLAYING TROMBONE]

1711
01:32:46,519 --> 01:32:47,853
Sounds good.

1712
01:32:48,188 --> 01:32:50,314
- It's progressive.
SHEPHERD: I'll say.

1713
01:32:50,482 --> 01:32:52,942
Dad, what's wrong with Sydney?
Did you have a fight?

1714
01:32:53,109 --> 01:32:54,151
What do you mean?

1715
01:32:54,319 --> 01:32:56,528
LUCY: She seemed pretty mad.
- You saw her?

1716
01:32:56,988 --> 01:32:58,322
- Yeah, she's here.
SHEPHERD: Where?

1717
01:32:58,490 --> 01:33:01,033
In your room. Dad, why's she mad?

1718
01:33:01,201 --> 01:33:02,910
Don't worry about it, honey.

1719
01:33:03,078 --> 01:33:05,329
LUCY: Were you a dork?
- Practice your music.

1720
01:33:05,497 --> 01:33:08,624
If you were a dork,
you should say you're sorry.

1721
01:33:08,792 --> 01:33:10,251
Girls like that.

1722
01:33:11,461 --> 01:33:13,212
Syd?

1723
01:33:13,380 --> 01:33:15,172
SYDNEY:
Did you see a gray cable-knit sweater?

1724
01:33:15,340 --> 01:33:16,382
Gray sweater? No.

1725
01:33:16,549 --> 01:33:18,092
I called you at the office today.

1726
01:33:18,260 --> 01:33:21,303
It's Beth's. I wore it here one time.
I didn't wanna leave it.

1727
01:33:21,471 --> 01:33:24,556
- Where are you going?
- I'm going home. Then to Hartford.

1728
01:33:24,724 --> 01:33:27,476
- Connecticut?
- Yes. Did it go with your dry cleaning?

1729
01:33:27,644 --> 01:33:28,978
What's in Connecticut?

1730
01:33:29,187 --> 01:33:31,939
Uh, Richard Reynolds' campaign.
He may be able to get a job.

1731
01:33:32,107 --> 01:33:33,941
When did you decide to get a new job?

1732
01:33:34,109 --> 01:33:36,986
Not long after Solomon fired me
from my old one.

1733
01:33:37,237 --> 01:33:40,364
- Beth's gonna kill me.
- Why did he fire you?

1734
01:33:40,532 --> 01:33:44,285
Oh, total failure to achieve
any of the objectives for which I was hired.

1735
01:33:44,452 --> 01:33:46,245
I told him he was being unreasonable.

1736
01:33:46,413 --> 01:33:51,083
After all, I did dance with the president
and ride in Air Force 1 a couple of times...

1737
01:33:51,251 --> 01:33:54,295
...but those prickly environmentalists.
There's always something.

1738
01:33:54,462 --> 01:33:56,380
If it's not clean air, it's clean water.

1739
01:33:56,548 --> 01:33:59,383
Like it's not enough
that I'm on the cover of People Magazine.

1740
01:33:59,551 --> 01:34:01,010
I'll call him.

1741
01:34:01,177 --> 01:34:03,387
You'll call him? You'll call him yourself?

1742
01:34:03,555 --> 01:34:05,723
It will come from the president?

1743
01:34:05,890 --> 01:34:08,976
That's a great idea.
You should call Leo and make a deal.

1744
01:34:09,144 --> 01:34:11,353
He hires me back for 72 days.

1745
01:34:11,521 --> 01:34:13,397
I go around scaring Congress...

1746
01:34:13,565 --> 01:34:17,401
...making them think the president will
drive through a damaging and costly bill.

1747
01:34:17,569 --> 01:34:21,113
They'll believe me because
I'm the president's Friday-night girl.

1748
01:34:21,281 --> 01:34:25,326
I don't know if we can dip into
that well twice. I've lost all credibility.

1749
01:34:25,493 --> 01:34:28,620
But you never know.
I might be able to pull it off again.

1750
01:34:28,788 --> 01:34:30,914
I might give you the leverage you need...

1751
01:34:31,082 --> 01:34:33,792
...to pass some ground-breaking piece
of crime legislation.

1752
01:34:33,960 --> 01:34:37,546
A mandatory three-day waiting period
before a 5-year-old can buy an Uzi.

1753
01:34:37,714 --> 01:34:41,008
Fuck the sweater. She'll have to learn
to live with disappointment.

1754
01:34:41,760 --> 01:34:43,969
What do you think went on here today?

1755
01:34:44,471 --> 01:34:47,890
I know exactly what went on here today.
I got screwed.

1756
01:34:48,058 --> 01:34:50,142
You saw the poll,
you needed the crime bill.

1757
01:34:50,310 --> 01:34:52,811
You couldn't get it on your own,
so I got screwed.

1758
01:34:52,979 --> 01:34:56,982
The environment got screwed, Sydney.
Nothing happened to you.

1759
01:34:57,150 --> 01:34:59,693
Governing is choosing.
Governing is prioritizing.

1760
01:34:59,861 --> 01:35:03,280
I made no secret of the fact
the crime bill was my top priority.

1761
01:35:03,448 --> 01:35:06,784
Well, then congratulations.
It's only taken you three years...

1762
01:35:06,951 --> 01:35:10,788
...to put together crime-prevention
legislation that won't prevent crime.

1763
01:35:10,955 --> 01:35:12,664
Syd, please.

1764
01:35:13,708 --> 01:35:15,834
I don't want to lose you over this.

1765
01:35:16,002 --> 01:35:20,297
Mr. President, you've got bigger problems
than losing me.

1766
01:35:21,216 --> 01:35:23,342
You just lost my vote.

1767
01:35:31,684 --> 01:35:32,810
What's in Hartford?

1768
01:35:32,977 --> 01:35:36,313
Richard Reynolds' district office.
She might run his campaign.

1769
01:35:36,481 --> 01:35:37,981
Twelve in the corner.

1770
01:35:38,149 --> 01:35:41,985
Hartford, the insurance capital
of the world.

1771
01:35:42,153 --> 01:35:44,696
Have a good time, Syd.

1772
01:35:45,490 --> 01:35:49,410
I'll have Janie clear your schedule for
the weekend. You need to get some rest.

1773
01:35:49,577 --> 01:35:51,954
- You handling me? Good.
- No, sir.

1774
01:35:52,122 --> 01:35:55,499
But I will if you don't start
taking your head out of your ass.

1775
01:35:56,668 --> 01:36:00,337
- Excuse me?
- Lewis is right. Go after this guy.

1776
01:36:02,382 --> 01:36:04,550
- Has he lied?
- What?

1777
01:36:04,717 --> 01:36:08,011
- Has Rumson lied in the past seven weeks?
- Has he lied?

1778
01:36:08,179 --> 01:36:11,348
Other than not knowing the difference
between Harvard and Stanford...

1779
01:36:11,516 --> 01:36:14,101
...has he said something
that isn't true?

1780
01:36:14,269 --> 01:36:17,354
Am I not a commander in chief
who's never served in the military?

1781
01:36:17,522 --> 01:36:21,775
Am I not opposed to a constitutional
amendment banning flag burning?

1782
01:36:21,943 --> 01:36:25,154
Am I not an unmarried father
sharing a bed with a liberal lobbyist...

1783
01:36:25,321 --> 01:36:28,407
...down the hall from his daughter?
- You think you're wrong?

1784
01:36:28,575 --> 01:36:31,702
You don't win by telling 59 percent of them
that they are.

1785
01:36:31,870 --> 01:36:35,747
"We fight the fights we can win"?
You fight the fights that need fighting!

1786
01:36:35,915 --> 01:36:38,834
Is the view pretty good
from the cheap seats, A. J?

1787
01:36:39,085 --> 01:36:40,335
I beg your pardon?

1788
01:36:40,503 --> 01:36:44,465
Because it occurs to me that in 25 years
I've never seen your name on a ballot.

1789
01:36:44,632 --> 01:36:47,885
Now, why is that?
Why are you always one step behind me?

1790
01:36:48,470 --> 01:36:51,305
If I wasn't, you'd be
the most popular history professor...

1791
01:36:51,473 --> 01:36:53,056
...at the University of Wisconsin.

1792
01:36:53,725 --> 01:36:55,350
Fuck you!

1793
01:37:00,190 --> 01:37:02,232
Have Lewis put the final draft...

1794
01:37:02,400 --> 01:37:05,611
...of the State of the Union
on my desk in the morning.

1795
01:37:06,070 --> 01:37:07,863
Yes, sir.

1796
01:37:17,624 --> 01:37:19,583
If Mary hadn't died...

1797
01:37:21,419 --> 01:37:24,129
...would we have won three years ago?

1798
01:37:25,882 --> 01:37:27,758
Would we have won?

1799
01:37:28,760 --> 01:37:32,513
If we had to go through a character debate
three years ago...

1800
01:37:32,680 --> 01:37:34,598
...would we have won?

1801
01:37:35,308 --> 01:37:37,184
I don't know.

1802
01:37:38,645 --> 01:37:41,480
But I would have liked that campaign.

1803
01:37:42,398 --> 01:37:44,399
If my friend, Andy Shepherd,
had shown up...

1804
01:37:44,567 --> 01:37:47,110
...I would have liked that campaign
very much.

1805
01:37:49,614 --> 01:37:51,281
Yeah.

1806
01:38:48,506 --> 01:38:52,843
ROBIN: Because the president feels there
is no value in this kind of character debate.

1807
01:38:53,052 --> 01:38:55,721
Will the president respond
to Senator Rumson's question...

1808
01:38:55,888 --> 01:38:58,390
...about being a member
of the American Civil Liberties Union?

1809
01:38:58,558 --> 01:39:01,977
Yes, he will. Good morning. It's all right.
Please keep your seats. Good morning.

1810
01:39:02,145 --> 01:39:04,813
[REPORTERS MURMURING]

1811
01:39:10,695 --> 01:39:13,572
For the last couple of months,
Senator Rumson has suggested...

1812
01:39:13,740 --> 01:39:18,076
...that being president of this country
was to a certain extent about character.

1813
01:39:18,661 --> 01:39:22,414
Although I have not been willing
to engage in his attacks on me...

1814
01:39:22,582 --> 01:39:26,335
...I've been here three years
and three days...

1815
01:39:26,586 --> 01:39:29,755
...and I can tell you without hesitation...

1816
01:39:29,922 --> 01:39:32,591
...being president of this country...

1817
01:39:32,759 --> 01:39:36,094
...is entirely about character.

1818
01:39:36,554 --> 01:39:38,013
For the record:

1819
01:39:38,181 --> 01:39:41,933
Yes, I am a card-carrying member
of the ACLU.

1820
01:39:42,101 --> 01:39:45,270
But the more important question is:
Why aren't you, Bob?

1821
01:39:45,438 --> 01:39:47,397
Now, this is an organization...

1822
01:39:47,649 --> 01:39:50,651
...whose sole purpose is to defend
the Bill of Rights.

1823
01:39:50,818 --> 01:39:53,779
So it naturally begs the question:
Why would a senator...

1824
01:39:53,946 --> 01:39:57,783
...his party's most powerful spokesman
and a candidate for president...

1825
01:39:57,950 --> 01:40:01,119
...choose to reject
upholding the Constitution?

1826
01:40:01,287 --> 01:40:05,123
Now, if you can answer that, folks,
then you're smarter than I am...

1827
01:40:05,291 --> 01:40:09,211
...because I didn't understand it
until a few hours ago.

1828
01:40:10,797 --> 01:40:12,964
America isn't easy.

1829
01:40:14,092 --> 01:40:18,136
America is advanced citizenship.
You've gotta want it bad...

1830
01:40:18,304 --> 01:40:20,514
...because it's gonna put up a fight.

1831
01:40:20,682 --> 01:40:23,183
It's gonna say, "You want free speech?

1832
01:40:23,351 --> 01:40:26,436
Let's see you acknowledge a man
whose words make your blood boil...

1833
01:40:26,604 --> 01:40:30,107
...who's standing center stage,
advocating at the top of his lungs...

1834
01:40:30,274 --> 01:40:33,944
...that which you would spend
a lifetime opposing at the top of yours.

1835
01:40:34,112 --> 01:40:36,571
You want to claim this land
as the land of the free?

1836
01:40:36,739 --> 01:40:40,117
Then the symbol of your country
cannot just be a flag.

1837
01:40:40,284 --> 01:40:41,993
The symbol also has to be...

1838
01:40:42,161 --> 01:40:47,124
...one of its citizens exercising his right
to burn that flag in protest.

1839
01:40:47,291 --> 01:40:51,086
Now, show me that, defend that,
celebrate that in your classrooms.

1840
01:40:51,254 --> 01:40:54,923
Then you can stand up
and sing about 'the land of the free."'

1841
01:40:55,258 --> 01:40:59,052
I've known Bob Rumson for years and
I've been operating under the assumption...

1842
01:40:59,220 --> 01:41:02,764
...that the reason Bob devotes
so much energy to shouting at the rain...

1843
01:41:02,932 --> 01:41:05,100
...was that he simply didn't get it.

1844
01:41:05,268 --> 01:41:08,520
Well, I was wrong.
Bob's problem isn't that he doesn't get it.

1845
01:41:08,688 --> 01:41:11,106
Bob's problem is that he can't sell it.

1846
01:41:12,692 --> 01:41:14,943
We have serious problems to solve...

1847
01:41:15,111 --> 01:41:17,779
...and we need serious people
to solve them.

1848
01:41:17,947 --> 01:41:21,450
And whatever your particular problem is,
I promise you...

1849
01:41:21,617 --> 01:41:25,746
...Bob Rumson is not the least bit
interested in solving it.

1850
01:41:25,913 --> 01:41:29,666
He is interested in two things
and two things only:

1851
01:41:29,834 --> 01:41:33,211
Making you afraid of it,
and telling you who's to blame for it.

1852
01:41:33,379 --> 01:41:36,089
That, ladies and gentlemen,
is how you win elections.

1853
01:41:36,716 --> 01:41:39,801
You gather a group of middle-aged,
middle-income voters...

1854
01:41:39,969 --> 01:41:43,013
...who remember with longing
an easier time. You talk to them...

1855
01:41:43,181 --> 01:41:46,349
...about family and American values
and character.

1856
01:41:46,517 --> 01:41:50,729
Then you wave an old photo of the
president's girlfriend, scream patriotism...

1857
01:41:50,897 --> 01:41:53,982
...tell them she's to blame
for their lot in life...

1858
01:41:54,150 --> 01:41:56,318
...and you go on television...

1859
01:41:56,486 --> 01:41:58,862
...and you call her a whore.

1860
01:41:59,822 --> 01:42:02,282
Sydney Ellen Wade
has done nothing to you, Bob.

1861
01:42:02,450 --> 01:42:05,786
She has done nothing
but put herself through school...

1862
01:42:05,995 --> 01:42:08,497
...represent the interest
of public-school teachers...

1863
01:42:08,664 --> 01:42:11,249
...and lobby for the safety
of our natural resources.

1864
01:42:11,417 --> 01:42:13,502
You want a character debate, Bob?

1865
01:42:13,669 --> 01:42:15,170
You better stick with me...

1866
01:42:15,338 --> 01:42:18,590
...because Sydney Ellen Wade
is way out of your league.

1867
01:42:26,098 --> 01:42:28,975
I've loved two women in my life.

1868
01:42:29,393 --> 01:42:31,728
I lost one to cancer...

1869
01:42:32,563 --> 01:42:35,857
...and I lost the other
because I was so busy keeping my job...

1870
01:42:36,025 --> 01:42:38,193
...I forgot to do my job.

1871
01:42:39,737 --> 01:42:41,571
Well, that ends right now.

1872
01:42:42,281 --> 01:42:43,532
Tomorrow morning...

1873
01:42:43,699 --> 01:42:47,702
...the White House is sending
a bill to Congress for its consideration.

1874
01:42:47,870 --> 01:42:50,413
It's White House Resolution 455...

1875
01:42:50,581 --> 01:42:53,959
...an energy bill,
requiring a 20 percent reduction...

1876
01:42:54,126 --> 01:42:57,546
...of the emission of fossil fuels
over the next 10 years.

1877
01:42:57,880 --> 01:43:01,716
It is by far the most aggressive stride
ever taken...

1878
01:43:02,009 --> 01:43:04,678
...in the fight to reverse
the effects of global warming.

1879
01:43:04,929 --> 01:43:08,265
The other piece of legislation
is the crime bill.

1880
01:43:09,433 --> 01:43:12,561
As of today, it no longer exists.

1881
01:43:12,728 --> 01:43:14,354
I'm throwing it out.

1882
01:43:14,522 --> 01:43:18,441
I'm throwing it out and writing a law
that makes sense.

1883
01:43:18,609 --> 01:43:20,902
You can't address crime prevention...

1884
01:43:21,070 --> 01:43:23,780
...without getting rid of assault weapons
and handguns.

1885
01:43:24,031 --> 01:43:27,117
I consider them a threat
to national security and I will go...

1886
01:43:27,285 --> 01:43:29,160
...door-to-door if I have to...

1887
01:43:29,328 --> 01:43:33,373
...but I'll convince Americans that I'm right
and I'm gonna get the guns.

1888
01:43:34,959 --> 01:43:39,004
We've got serious problems
and we need serious people.

1889
01:43:39,171 --> 01:43:41,506
If you want to talk about character,
Bob...

1890
01:43:41,674 --> 01:43:45,343
...you'd better come at me with more
than a burning flag and a membership card.

1891
01:43:45,511 --> 01:43:48,889
If you want to talk about character
and American values, fine.

1892
01:43:49,056 --> 01:43:51,892
Just tell me where and when
and I'll show up.

1893
01:43:52,059 --> 01:43:56,104
This is a time for serious people, Bob,
and your 15 minutes are up.

1894
01:43:56,272 --> 01:43:59,649
My name is Andrew Shepherd
and I am the president.

1895
01:44:01,402 --> 01:44:04,571
[ALL SHOUTING]

1896
01:44:08,784 --> 01:44:10,452
Well, you don't see that every day.

1897
01:44:10,620 --> 01:44:13,455
He's got the whole press corps asking
how to spell "erudite."

1898
01:44:13,623 --> 01:44:16,374
- Call the printer.
- We gotta rewrite the State of the Union.

1899
01:44:16,542 --> 01:44:19,002
A. J:
Every word. It's a whole new ball game.

1900
01:44:19,170 --> 01:44:20,837
You have exactly 35 minutes.

1901
01:44:21,005 --> 01:44:23,924
Oh, good.
I thought it was gonna be rushed.

1902
01:44:24,550 --> 01:44:26,927
I don't want a limousine,
I don't want an escort.

1903
01:44:27,094 --> 01:44:30,597
I want a plain ordinary,
non-bulletproof automobile.

1904
01:44:30,765 --> 01:44:33,725
Well, somebody around here
must have a Chevy I can borrow.

1905
01:44:33,893 --> 01:44:37,854
Well, find one and have it outside
the West Wing entrance in five minutes.

1906
01:44:38,022 --> 01:44:39,689
A. J:
Excuse me, sir, where are you going?

1907
01:44:39,857 --> 01:44:43,818
I'm going over to her house. I'm gonna
stand outside her door till she lets me in.

1908
01:44:43,986 --> 01:44:45,904
I'm not leaving until I get her back.

1909
01:44:46,072 --> 01:44:48,365
And how are you going to do that, sir?

1910
01:44:48,532 --> 01:44:51,826
I haven't worked that out yet.
But I'm sure groveling will be involved.

1911
01:44:52,119 --> 01:44:53,536
You're just gonna drive over?

1912
01:44:53,704 --> 01:44:56,665
I'm commander in chief
of the most powerful army in the world.

1913
01:44:56,832 --> 01:44:59,250
You don't think I can drive 10 blocks?

1914
01:44:59,877 --> 01:45:03,838
Just, uh, stay away from Dupont Circle.
I hear it's murder this time of day.

1915
01:45:09,929 --> 01:45:11,304
Hi, A.J.

1916
01:45:12,056 --> 01:45:14,015
Nice to see you, Miss Wade.

1917
01:45:20,606 --> 01:45:23,900
Well, if anyone needs me,
I'll be in the Roosevelt Room...

1918
01:45:24,110 --> 01:45:26,069
...giving Lewis oxygen.

1919
01:45:30,282 --> 01:45:31,574
I heard your speech.

1920
01:45:35,204 --> 01:45:37,622
I was in my car.

1921
01:45:39,083 --> 01:45:42,127
It just kind of steered its way over here.

1922
01:45:43,963 --> 01:45:45,296
I'm glad.

1923
01:45:53,723 --> 01:45:54,889
Sydney...

1924
01:45:55,599 --> 01:45:59,811
I didn't decide to send 455 to the floor
to get you back.

1925
01:46:00,604 --> 01:46:04,607
And I didn't come back
because you sent 455 to the floor.

1926
01:46:11,282 --> 01:46:13,658
Mr. President, you might want to...

1927
01:46:14,910 --> 01:46:15,952
Hi, Sydney.

1928
01:46:16,579 --> 01:46:18,371
Hi.

1929
01:46:19,874 --> 01:46:21,583
I moved Social Security up front.

1930
01:46:21,751 --> 01:46:25,211
Mr. Leventhal at Treasury wants
two minutes. Hello, Sydney.

1931
01:46:25,379 --> 01:46:29,799
Mr. President? Excuse me, Miss Wade.
Miss McCall is on her way over, sir.

1932
01:46:30,843 --> 01:46:32,802
Well, I got some...

1933
01:46:32,970 --> 01:46:34,471
...things to do.

1934
01:46:35,765 --> 01:46:37,265
Yes, you do.

1935
01:46:38,768 --> 01:46:41,770
REPORTER: We're only a moment away
from the arrival of President Shepherd...

1936
01:46:41,937 --> 01:46:43,438
...and his State of the Union address.

1937
01:46:43,606 --> 01:46:46,524
You've served on the staffs
of several past administrations.

1938
01:46:46,692 --> 01:46:50,904
What kind of last-minute activity
is the president engaged in right now?

1939
01:46:56,911 --> 01:47:00,080
There's something I've wanted to give you
since our first date.

1940
01:47:00,247 --> 01:47:03,875
I've tried to do it a number of times,
but somehow I've always managed...

1941
01:47:04,043 --> 01:47:05,877
...to trip over my job...

1942
01:47:06,170 --> 01:47:08,171
...but here...

1943
01:47:08,339 --> 01:47:09,631
...these are for you.

1944
01:47:09,799 --> 01:47:11,591
[CHUCKLES]

1945
01:47:13,052 --> 01:47:14,636
They're beautiful.

1946
01:47:18,182 --> 01:47:20,475
Ahem, Mr. President?

1947
01:47:20,643 --> 01:47:22,143
Well, I've gotta go.

1948
01:47:22,311 --> 01:47:24,312
Uh, should I stay here?

1949
01:47:25,731 --> 01:47:27,315
Walk with me.

1950
01:47:32,029 --> 01:47:33,363
SYDNEY:
How'd you finally do it?

1951
01:47:34,532 --> 01:47:35,824
Do what?

1952
01:47:35,991 --> 01:47:39,619
Manage to give a woman flowers
and be president at the same time?

1953
01:47:39,787 --> 01:47:43,123
Well, it turns out I've got a rose garden.

1954
01:47:45,626 --> 01:47:47,377
MAN: Mr. Speaker.
- Heh.

1955
01:47:47,545 --> 01:47:50,964
The president of the United States!

1956
01:47:51,423 --> 01:47:53,424
[INAUDIBLE DIALOGUE]

1957
01:53:13,537 --> 01:53:15,538
[English - US - SDH]

